<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats To Raise $4M Thursday  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A star-studded fund-raising gala at the end
of the Democratic National Convention will bring in at least $4
million, party sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   All of the money raised Thursday evening will fall under federal
contribution limits -- so-called ''hard money'' -- meaning the
Democratic National Committee can spend it directly on candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The gala is to be hosted by actress Whoopi Goldberg and feature
entertainment by Barbra Streisand, Enrique Iglesias, Baby Face and
Boyz II Men.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets will range from $150 to $20,000 -- the maximum annual
contribution an individual can make to a political party under
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Co-chairs will raise $50,000 and vice chairs will raise or
donate $20,000 for the event, scheduled for the Shrine Auditorium,
home of the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The event is the first in a series of concerts with low ticket
prices Democrats hope to stage this fall based on the success of a
May 24 fund-raiser that raised a record $26.5 million and attracted
more than 12,000 people. The entertainment included Stevie Wonder,
Lenny Kravitz and Robin Williams. While the top ticket price was
$500,000, thousands of $50 tickets sold as well.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also hope to close the gap in hard money fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Through June 30, the Republican National Committee had $21.1
million in hard money in the bank, compared to just $9.3 million
for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   At their convention two weeks ago in Philadelphia, Republicans
raised $10 million at a gala on George W. Bush's first day at the
convention. That total, however, was a combination of hard money,
which fell under donor limits, and unlimited soft money
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   While the party increases its take of money raised under federal
contribution limits, it also is recognizing its biggest donors of
soft money, the unregulated contributions from labor unions,
corporations and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   During convention week, the party has set up a ''chairman's
circle'' to recognize donors of at least $500,000. The list
includes trial lawyer Peter Angelos, owner of the Baltimore
Orioles; S. Daniel Abraham, former owner of Slim Fast; and several
labor unions, including the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-16-00 0033 </TRAILER>
