<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Leaders End Congo Summit  </HEADLINE>
By MILDRED MULENGA
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) -- Weary African leaders wound up 18 hours of
talks in Zambia early Tuesday without reaching an agreement on how
to revive the crumbling Congo peace accord, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Congolese President Laurent Kabila and his two key military
allies, President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe and Namibian leader Sam
Nujoma, departed in the early hours Tuesday, leaving chief mediator
President Frederick Chiluba of Zambia to close the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Chiluba said Kabila resisted calls for him to allow the
unhindered deployment of U.N. monitors and accept former Botswana
President Sir Ketumile Masire as ''facilitator'' for an internal
political dialogue between the Congolese government and rebels
fighting to oust him.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila has accused Masire, appointed by the continent-wide
Organization of African Unity, of bias toward the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Chiluba said he was confident Kabila would still comply with
U.N. conditions. ''The Congo wants (U.N.) troops in the country, I
have no doubt about that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chiluba said regional sanctions on the Congo were not foreseen,
but remained an option to force Kabila to accept Masire.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing disappointment at the failure of a summit, U.S.
deputy ambassador to the U.N. Nancy Soderberg said that the United
States on Tuesday urged Kabila to honor the year-old peace
agreement and end the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Soderberg told the U.N. Security Council the United States was
encouraged there was a consensus by non-Congolese signatories of
the agreement on measures to revive the crumbling peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are disappointed that the government of the Congo was not
among the consensus of this group and continues to oppose full
implementation of the Lusaka agreement,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting in Congo broke out in August 1998 with rebels
backed by Rwanda and Uganda accusing Kabila of corruption and of
harboring Hutu militiamen who fled Rwanda after committing genocide
there in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila and his allies -- Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- signed a
cease-fire agreement last year with Rwanda, Uganda and the rebels.
But the fighting has continued.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has proposed deploying a monitoring force of
5,537 observers and troops to oversee the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council mandate for the force is up for renewal at
the end of this month and will likely be suspended if Kabila does
not yield, leading to fears of a sharp escalation in fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila, who angered even his close allies by staying away from a
regional economic summit last week, was the last of 10 African
presidents to arrive at a convention center in Lusaka on Monday for
the biggest gathering of high-level officials on the Congo
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   South African President Thabo Mbeki and other leaders of
countries not directly involved in the war went to their hotels
after seven hours of closed-door talks Monday. But the warring
parties and Chiluba kept meeting late into the night to discuss
ways to enforce a cease-fire, withdraw forces and foster political
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence of a deal was never high among residents listening
for radio news in Kinshasha, 620 miles away from the nearest
battles in Congo. One woman who gave her name only as Azama said
the meeting was ''just a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices are high, pay is low, and disillusion with Kabila's
government -- which came to power just three years ago after ending
the decades-long rule of dictator Mobutu Sese Seko -- has become
increasingly profound. Politicians are regularly arrested,
newspapers are closed and police harassment is once again the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ''This war makes us live in the Congo as if we were foreigners
in our country,'' said Dan Kilosho, a construction worker. ''Our
rights are just not respected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-16-00 0033 </TRAILER>
