<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressChristine Dillon Denning:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Christine ''Auntie Doll'' Dillon Denning,
whose ''message in a bottle'' story was recently featured in The
Times-Picayune and distributed by The Associated Press across the
South, died Monday. She was 100.
</P>
<P>
   Denning, known for her precise diction, energy and interest in
other people, never revealed to her family that she had a
trans-Atlantic pen pal. Relatives only recently turned up the stash
of letters that revealed the relationship that began when Denning,
then 28, tossed a bottle into the ocean with a note tucked inside.
</P>
<P>
   She was known affectionately as ''The Lady from the U.S.'' by
the poor Irish boy who found her bottle and with whom she
corresponded for five years. She often tucked gifts of money into
her letters.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Denning was an executive with the American
Red Cross and later held a position with the Red Cross in Miami
where she was involved in the repatriation of men who had been
captured in the Bay of Pigs invasion.
Fred Gebhardt:
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Fred Gebhardt, Germany's oldest member
of parliament, who left the Social Democrats to protest their move
to the center and joined the former East German communist party,
died Monday after a long illness. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Gebhardt left the Social Democrats, the party of Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder, in 1998 after 52 years in protest against the
left-wing party's shift toward the center, which he termed a change
in course ''from an employees' to a neo-liberal business party.''
</P>
<P>
   He had also served as Hesse's Social Democratic chairman, based
in Frankfurt, where he headed an adult education school.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1998, he was elected to the Bundestag, or lower
house, for the former communists and gave the speech opening
parliament, traditionally delivered by the oldest legislator. He
also served on the human rights committee.
Leonard Kwan:
</P>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- Leonard Kwan, a master of slack key guitar whose
composition ''Opihi Moemoe'' is considered a classic of the genre,
died Monday in his sleep. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan began recording in 1957 and most recently recorded two
albums for George Winston's Dancing Cat Records. The second will be
released in September.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan also was the first slack key guitarist to publicly share
his instrument tunings in an instruction book.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaiian slack key, or ki ho'alu, is a unique musical style
dating to the 1830s, when Spanish and Mexican cowboys arrived in
the islands. Some of the guitar strings are slacked from the
standard tuning and songs are played in a finger-picking style,
with the thumb playing bass.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, he recorded, ''Slack Key,'' the world's first
all-instrumental slack key album.
John Milford:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- John Milford, a character actor who had roles
in about 500 television productions and a dozen theatrical films,
has died. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Milford collapsed and died Monday while en route to his nearby
home after outpatient treatment for skin cancer in Santa Monica,
said publicist Dale C. Olson.
</P>
<P>
   The actor, who made his film debut in ''Marty,'' had television
guest roles in dozens of popular series over 40 years including
''The X-Files,'' ''MacGyver,'' ''Dallas,'' ''Quincy,'' ''Cagney &AMP;
Lacey,'' ''Dynasty,'' ''Highway to Heaven,'' ''Picket Fences'' and
''Melrose Place.'' As one of ''The Mighty Carson Players,'' he
appeared opposite Johnny Carson on ''The Tonight Show,'' playing
Russian leader Leonid Brezhnev to Carson's Ronald Reagan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-16-00 0038 </TRAILER>
