<HEADLINE> 18 Die in Oil Fire in South Uganda  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- A fire ignited as villagers scooped fuel
oil from an overturned tanker in southern Uganda, killing at least
18 people, a newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred in a papyrus swamp Sunday evening along
the Kampala-Masaka highway, 25 miles southwest of Kampala, the
independent New Vision newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said more than 30 men were scooping oil spilled on the
road when the fire ignited, according to the daily. Dozens of acres
of swamp burned before firefighters extinguished the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were trying to get fuel from the water. I don't know what
happened,'' District Police Commander Ebiyu, was quoted as saying.
He did not provide his first name.
</P>
<P>
   But witnesses said one person struck a match after a
disagreement over how the oil would be shared, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel tanker, which had Kenyan registration, was transporting
the oil to Rwanda.
</P>
</TEXT>
