<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Mocks Bush, Hails Gore  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN SOLOMON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Warmly embraced by the delegates who had
turned him aside, former Sen. Bill Bradley mocked George W. Bush's
compassionate conservatism on Tuesday and accused Republicans of
wanting to ''give the fruits of our hard-won prosperity to those
who don't need the help.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who quit the rough-and-tumble primary race against Al
Gore five months ago, took the podium at the Democratic National
Convention and immediately went to work to make the case for his
former rival.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me get right to the point,'' he began. ''We're all here to
elect the next president of the United States, Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's absolutely essential that we get behind Al Gore. I
support him. I endorse him. I'll work hard for his victory,''
Bradley said in a speech in which he didn't mention Gore after the
fifth paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   He said his quest for the presidency had been ''a joyous
journey, and I have the scars to prove it,'' drawing a knowing
chuckle from the crowd. Blue signs proclaiming simply ''Bill
Bradley'' fluttered throughout the hall.
</P>
<P>
   The former professional basketball star spent most of his speech
pressing his pet issues -- campaign reform, universal health and
eliminating poverty -- and sharply attacking Republicans for what he
said was a facade of compassion at their recent convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't window-dress diversity. We're the party of
diversity,'' he declared. ''We don't declare ourselves to be
compassionate. We've been acting compassionately for decades. We
don't just talk about prosperity -- we make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Without ever mentioning Bush, he repeatedly mocked the
Republican's campaign slogan.
</P>
<P>
   ''As Democrats, we're not conservative with our compassion. At
our best, we give it generously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He described the fall election as a ''choice between a
Republican Party that is determined to give the fruits of our
hard-won prosperity to those who don't need the help, and a
Democratic Party that promises to use this great opportunity to
provide care for the ill, to lift up millions from poverty, to heal
the wounds of racial divide and to ensure that every child has a
decent public school.''
</P>
<P>
   But while President Clinton and Gore have tried to make economic
prosperity the theme of the convention, Bradley listed several
statistics suggesting not all is well in America -- 44 million
without health insurance and 13 million children living in poverty.
The reference made Republicans gleeful.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I were Al Gore I would be livid,'' Republican New Jersey
Gov. Christine Todd Whitman said, ''since the theme of the
convention is 'Are you better off today than 8 years ago,' and he's
saying just the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley made passing reference to the sharp disagreements that
surfaced during the primaries -- battles left behind several weeks
ago when he endorsed the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you run against someone you get to know him very well,''
Bradley conceded. ''I learned that Al Gore is a man of wide-ranging
intellect, with a deep desire to serve, profound preparation for
the job, a strong sense of loyalty, and a life view infused with
tolerance and rooted in religious faith.
</P>
<P>
   ''What strikes me is that we share so much more than what we
disagree on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley urged Democrats to seize the issues he championed as a
senator from New Jersey and a presidential candidate -- health care,
fighting poverty, campaign finance reform among them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every generation has to fight for democracy in its own way,''
he said. ''Our fight is campaign finance reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
