<HEADLINE> Kerrey: Clinton Must Let Gore Lead  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN O'HANLON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Sen. Bob Kerrey said Tuesday that President
Clinton must step aside and let Al Gore have the political
spotlight if he is to convince Americans he's ready to lead them.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he doesn't, it will be very difficult for Al Gore to win,''
said Kerrey, a Democrat who has clashed with Clinton in the past.
''He's not only got to get off the stage, he's got to allow the
vice president to say 'I'm a different person and I am going to do
things differently.'''
</P>
<P>
   ''Al Gore needs to be allowed to take center stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived in Los Angeles last Friday, attended several
parties and helped raise money for Hillary Rodham Clinton's New
York Senate campaign before delivering his farewell address Monday
night to the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president gave a very good speech, a very moving speech,''
Kerrey said. ''He's entitled to come to the convention and speak,
but he's got to -- between now and the election -- move aside and let
the Democratic nominee lead this party.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Richard Nixon in 1960 and Hubert Humphrey in 1968 were
never able to emerge from the shadows cast by presidents Eisenhower
and Johnson, and lost their White House bids those years.
</P>
</TEXT>
