<HEADLINE> Jackson Raises the Roof at DNC  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Jesse Jackson led cheering Democrats in
chants of ''stay out the Bushes'' Tuesday night as he blasted
Republicans as a ''grizzly old team'' that wants to give tax breaks
to the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is more with Gore,'' Jackson declared at the Democratic
National Convention, ''more health care with Gore, more education
with Gore ... more wages with Gore, more freedom with Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I say America, stay out the Bushes, stay out the Bushes,'' he
chanted as the audience shouted along in a refrain against
Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat presidential candidate Al Gore ''stood up for justice''
when he chose Sen. Joe Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, as his running
mate, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Al Gore has brought the sons and daughters of slaves and
slavemasters together with the sons and daughters of Holocaust
survivors. He raised the moral chin bar,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign issued a tart response.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Vice President Gore was serious about renouncing personal
attacks and unkind words, he shouldn't have allowed his surrogates
to do it for him,'' Bush campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer said.
''The American people will not support old-style attack politics,
and tonight's speech will be remembered as the type of partisanship
and bitterness the country would prefer to leave behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson told the delegates, ''This fall there will be two teams
on the field: two teams, two plans, two directions.'' He warned
that the Republicans are trying to blur the differences between the
parties, adding, ''don't be fooled, just look at the team.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not just Bush and Cheney but grizzled old veterans such
as Jesse Helms and Dick Armey and Tom DeLay and Bob Barr and Strom
Thurmond,'' Jackson said to boos and hisses from the audience.
</P>
