<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats' Keynoter: Harold Ford Jr  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Harold Ford Jr., a rising black star of the
South, said a Democratic victory in the fall would energize a new
generation of voters while ''some in the other party would have us
go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 30, a centrist Democrat from Al Gore's home state of
Tennessee, was cast in Tuesday night's keynote role to help the
Democratic presidential ticket appeal to young voters and
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, the youngest member of Congress, said, ''I recognize that
I stand here tonight because of the brave men and women, many no
older than I am today, who fought and stood and often times sat
down to create that perfect union.''
</P>
<P>
   ''But I also stand here representing a new generation,'' the
Memphis congressman said.
</P>
<P>
   Like both Gore and Republican nominee George W. Bush, Ford is
the son of a prominent politician and has struggled to step out
from his father's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ''I say to those of this new generation, I say to all Americans
who share our spirit, if you want a future that belongs to you, if
you want a future that is for everyone, then join with us and make
Al Gore our next president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is faring much better than Gore among young voters, polls
show. Though holding a wide lead among minorities, the vice
president needs to strengthen his bond with traditional Democratic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   The son of liberal former Rep. Harold Ford, the two-term
lawmaker has reached for the political middle. He hopes to win
statewide office, breaking ground for a black in Tennessee, and may
someday seek a national post.
</P>
<P>
   He has supported free trade, capital gains tax cuts and a
constitutional amendment protecting school prayer -- placing him
well to the right of his father's generation of black leaders. He
is a member of the New Democratic Coalition, a centrist caucus, and
has clashed with the more liberal House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   Ford criticized President Clinton for his affair with Monica
Lewinsky, even as most black leaders rallied behind the president.
</P>
<P>
   Even Republicans say Ford's stock is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a comer in Tennessee,'' said Tom Ingram, who worked for
former Republican presidential candidate Lamar Alexander. ''He's
got significant talents. He presents well. He is very articulate.
He comes from a rich political heritage, but he is seen as going
beyond it and seems to have a good bit of political savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford himself believes the sky is the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Asked this week about his political future, Ford lifted his arm
toward the ceiling and said, ''If this is the trajectory I'm on, I
like where I'm going.''
</P>
<P>
   In the address that introduced him to a nation, Ford listed
Gore's accomplishments -- including the vice president's work as a
30-something lawmaker to improve the environment, strengthen the
military and clean up the political system. ''Some pose for reform
and photo ops, but Al Gore is ready to sign a campaign reform
bill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reference to Bush, not his only one: Ford also said
America ''needs a leader with intellect to understand the
complexities we face, a leader with experience who can grasp the
challenges of our world.'' Voters tell pollsters they wonder
whether Bush is up to the job.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up the convention's theme, Ford said electing Bush would
return America to the era of former President George Bush, when he
said prosperity didn't trickle down to the poor, educational
opportunities were limited, polluters wrote environmental laws and
the economy was run ''into the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Times are good now, he said, ''but some in the other party would
have us go back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-16-00 0047 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
