<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nets Love Lure of Kennedys' Camelot  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A chance to revisit Camelot is a trip to
heaven for television, and Caroline Kennedy gave networks all the
excuse they needed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Film libraries were mined for nostalgic footage of Kennedy's
handsome and tragedy-filled political family to mark her appearance
at the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''We remember not just the battles but the glamour, the style,
the charm of them all,'' CNN's Bruce Morton commented over images
that proved his point.
</P>
<P>
   There was first lady Jacqueline Kennedy, elegant in riding gear
and leading a horse carrying a tiny Caroline. There were Caroline
and her father aboard a ship, she nestled in his lap and both
bathed in sunshine on a tranquil sea.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe there was, however briefly, a place called Camelot. A
child who lived there speaks to the Democrats tonight,'' Morton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a real place in the Democratic heart for the Kennedys,
isn't there?'' CNN anchor Judy Woodruff asked analyst Jeff
Greenfield, who was a speechwriter for Robert Kennedy when the
senator was assassinated in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is,'' he replied, citing the sheer number of Kennedys in
politics and the fact they've been part of every Democratic
convention since 1956. Then he got to the emotional core.
</P>
<P>
   By the time President Kennedy was killed in Dallas in 1963,
television was a fixture in most American homes. ''For the first
time, the country mourned in front of a TV set,'' Greenfield said,
creating an enduring national memory.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, Foxnews.com called Caroline Kennedy's
appearance ''fraught with meaning,'' noting that Los Angeles was
where her father was nominated and where her uncle was shot after
winning the 1968 California presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   The normally private Kennedy was ready for her close-up. She was
undoubtedly a reluctant surrogate, forced into action by the plane
crash death of her brother, John F. Kennedy Jr., a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   A slender figure in a simple white dress, the telegenic Kennedy
got a rousing welcome from convention delegates when she appeared
on the podium to give a brief speech that introduced her uncle,
Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ''As I look out across this hall and across this country, I know
that my father's spirit lives on, and I thank all of you,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thank all Americans for making me and John and all our
family a part of your families, for reaching out and sustaining us
through the good times and the difficult ones and for helping us
dream my father's dream.''
</P>
<P>
   TV analysts went to work even as Kennedy took the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's trying to recapture for the Democratic Party and her
family the legacy of John Kennedy,'' Tim Russert said on MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   But in post-speech appearances, Caroline Kennedy put a different
spin on her rare public appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is a really important election,'' she told
Woodruff on CNN, citing issues including health care, education and
potential Supreme Court appointments.
</P>
<P>
   For a second night, the convention ran past TV primetime in the
East. While broadcasters were willing to stay with President
Clinton until about 11:40 p.m. EDT on Monday, CBS and ABC cut away
at 11 p.m. EDT from Tuesday night's final speaker, Rep. Harold Ford
Jr. of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   NBC News, covering the night via cable's MSNBC, remained with
the convention until its conclusion at 11:08 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Making the news show rounds earlier Tuesday, Caroline Kennedy
batted away Dan Rather's question on CBS about a future political
career. ''Well, I'd just like to get through tonight,'' she said,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about her image as the reclusive Kennedy, she told NBC's
Claire Shipman ''I do get around, I do get out of my house.''
</P>
<P>
   Her typical refusal to pander to the media made her all the more
the object of its interest.
</P>
<P>
   Cokie Roberts, hosting a segment on ''Kennedys in the
Spotlight'' on the Internet for ABC News, asked Rep. Marty Meehan,
D-Mass., why Kennedy would appear at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well I think that she feels a responsibility as the only
person left from that great family to send a message that her
father would want to be sent here,'' Meehan said. ''And I think she
feels added responsibility because her brother is no longer here.
... I think she feels that it's part of being a Kennedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
