<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carnegie Mellon robotics team hopes to score at strange soccer competition </HEADLINE>
By JOE MANDAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) - Sportswriter Grantland Rice couldn't have
envisioned Robocup2000, but he penned the perfect cliche to
describe it: It matters ''not that you won or lost, but how you
played the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Robotics Institute at Carnegie Mellon
University are competing in the worldwide soccer tournament that
pits 150 computer-simulated and robotic teams from 35 countries
against one another in Melbourne, Australia, Aug. 26 to Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers are hoping the technology they use to build
their teams will help them construct better computers - computers
that can solve problems and make decisions on their own, while also
working together as a team, just like the players on a soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like the Apollo space program. There was a very concrete
goal of landing on the moon, but to do that, you're going to have
to develop a lot of technologies that are generally applicable
outside the space program,'' said Peter Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Stone is a research scientist at AT&AMP;T laboratories in Florham
Park, N.J., who co-founded the first-ever Robocup in 1996 while
still at CMU. Stone heads the ATT-CMUnited virtual soccer team that
is part of a $1.5 million program funded by the Defense Advanced
Research Projects Agency, a military group dedicated to robotics
and computer design.
</P>
<P>
   Stone says soccer players are continually making split-second
decisions: whether and where to run, pass and shoot. And they must
do so in concert with 11 other teammates.
</P>
<P>
   In computerese, teaching a machine to make split-second
decisions is called layered learning.
</P>
<P>
   ''You (rewrite the program) to increase the probability that the
action that was just taken will be taken again in the same
situation,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters is that each player on Stone's virtual
soccer team is running on a separate program that must cooperate
with the others on his team - and against a team designed to thwart
its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   So how can a computerized soccer game help AT&AMP;T?
</P>
<P>
   Take e-mail, for example. There is no direct pipeline from one
e-mail ''box'' to another - rather, computers route e-mails over a
variety of ever-changing networks.
</P>
<P>
   By writing programs that enable computers to make routing
decisions based on changing conditions - much like a soccer player
dodges a defender or passes to a teammate - e-mail and other
Internet traffic will be more efficient, Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Another variable is when artificial intelligence is married to
robotics.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Emery is one of a team of graduate students at CMU who
will enter a soccer team consisting of four robots in Robocup2000s'
''medium-size'' league for robots that are about the size of a
bread box.
</P>
<P>
   The teams play on a carpeted field measuring 9 by 5 meters, with
color-coded goals at both ends. The robots move on motorized
trailers that have cameras allowing each ''player'' to ''see'' the
ball and the goals.
</P>
<P>
   These preprogrammed robots then share that information with one
another and move about - at about one meter per second - in an
effort to nudge an orange ball into their goal, while preventing
their opponent from doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   All the factors Stone must consider are present - but the
computerized soccer commands are now being carried out by robots,
not ''virtual'' players on a video screen.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, more technology comes into play, including
odometry, a robot's ability to tell where it is at a given moment.
Soccer robots calculate their location based on how much their
wheels spin, which means a robot can become ''lost'' if it is
knocked around by a moving ball or a rampaging opponent, Emery
said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are developing technology that allows the robots to
link that odometry information with the data they ''see'' through
their cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ''Using the two, the robots can calculate where they believe
they are,'' Emery said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.cs.cmu.edu/(tilde)multirobotlab/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.research.att.com./(tilde)pstone/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.Robocup2000.org/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.darpa.mil/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
