<HEADLINE> Twins 6, Royals 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Eric Milton won his fourth straight decision,
and Torii Hunter homered and drove in three runs Tuesday night as
the Minnesota Twins beat the Kansas City Royals 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Jacque Jones also homered for Minnesota, which has won seven of
its last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sweeney homered and drove in two runs for the Royals, who
lost their seventh straight game at the Metrodome dating to last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Milton (12-6) allowed two runs and five hits in seven-plus
innings, improving to 4-0 with a 1.95 ERA in his last five starts.
He has allowed 22 hits and struck out 28 in that span, pitch 37
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Wells pitched two perfect innings for his ninth save in 15
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Suppan (6-7) allowed four runs and nine hits in seven
innings, losing for the first time in eight starts since June 25.
He had won four straight decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's Johnny Damon, who entered hitting .471
(64-for-136) since the All-Star break, was 1-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota took a 1-0 lead on Ron Coomer's RBI single in the
first, and Jones homered in the second, his team-leading 17th.
David Ortiz's sacrifice fly in the third made it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney hit a solo homer off Milton in the sixth, giving him 20
homers and 101 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Corey Koskie led off the bottom of the inning with a double and
Hunter drove him in with a single.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney's RBI groundout in the eighth made it 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter hit a two-run homer, his third home run in the three
games, off Jerry Spradlin in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth inning, Ortiz hit a high pop that was going foul
behind the plate, before it hit a speaker and was redirected into
play. Suppan caught the ball off the speaker in foul territory for
an out.
</P>
<P>
   Twins right fielder Matt Lawton made a nice catch in the
seventh, leaping against the wall to catch David McCarty's fly
ball.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Twins manager Tom Kelly celebrated his 50th birthday. ...
After getting his first win of the year against Minnesota on April
8, Suppan went eight starts without a victory. ... McCarty was
Minnesota's No. 1 draft choice in 1991. ... Denny Hocking went
3-for-3 for Minnesota. ... Hunter is hitting .379 in 16 games since
being recalled from Triple-A Salt Lake on July 29. ... Kansas
City's Carlos Beltran, who was suspended without pay, for not
reporting for a rehab assignment, received only a partial amount of
his salary on the first payday since the suspension. Kansas City
expects the players' association to file a default notice with the
commissioner's office. The Royals would then pay Beltran, pending a
grievance hearing, and would deduct the money in the future if an
arbitrator rules in their favor.
</P>
