<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Rowing Squad Finalized  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Two-time Olympians Jeff Klepacki and Bob
Kaehler, both members of the United States' men's eight crew that
has won three straight world championships, were among those
selected Tuesday for the team that will compete in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rowing officials also picked the women's quadruple sculls
crew that finished third at the World Cup in Switzerland this
summer as its Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is the only country to qualify a full
contingent of 14 boats and 48 athletes for Sydney. Those selected
Tuesday were the final members chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Kaehler was part of all three world championships while Klepacki
was on two. Brown sophomore Dave Simon was the lone newcomer chosen
by men's sweep coach Mike Teti.
</P>
<P>
   Coxswain Pete Cipollone, Chris Ahrens and Garrett Miller also
were part of all three world championship crews. Porter Collins,
Tom Welsh and Bryan Volpenhein were on the last two. Collins will
be participating in his second Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The United States hasn't won a gold medal in the men's eight
since 1964. Americans have earned silver in 1972 and '84 and bronze
in '88 after winning 10 golds in the 12 Olympics from 1900-56.
</P>
<P>
   Laurel Korholz and Jennifer Dore-Terhaar were part of the
women's eight that finished fourth at the 1996 Olympics. They'll be
joined in Sydney by Kelly Salchow and Hilary Gehman.
</P>
<P>
   The foursome finished fourth at the 1999 world championships in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has never won an Olympic medal in the women's
quadruple sculls, although an American crew did win a silver medal
in the quad with coxswain in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, both squads have only been nominated. They will
officially be selected when the U.S. Olympic Committee gives final
approval later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Finals for both Olympic events will be Sept. 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
