<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advocates won't try again after N.J. Supreme Court strikes down notification law </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Abortion opponents said there was not much
point to revising New Jersey's law requiring minors to notify a
parent before they can get an abortion following the Supreme Court
decision to strike it down.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins said he saw no room to tighten the
statute he had sponsored and that Gov. Christie Whitman saw fit to
sign even though she is an advocate of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know how much more limited it could be,'' Collins
said. Whitman herself issued a brief statement saying the law she
signed ''to increase parental involvement in a minor's decision to
have an abortion'' had been balanced and fair.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Tasy of New Jersey Right To Life, which argued for the law
in court, said the law she helped shepherd through the Legislature
was as limited as it could be and still function.
</P>
<P>
   Tasy said the state Supreme Court showed in its 4-2 ruling
Tuesday it would be unwilling to accept any version of parental
notification, and the best effort now would be get around the
Supreme Court by inserting the rule into the state's constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had all the bases covered,'' Tasy said. ''It appears that
the only remedy this is to take the courts completely out of the
equation, and it looks like it may be time to change the state
constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Deborah Poritz in her majority opinion said the
parental-notification law was unconstitutional ''because a minor's
right to control her reproductive decisions is among the most
fundamental of the rights she possesses,'' and the state failed to
show it had a good reason to interfere with those rights.
</P>
<P>
   A Superior Court judge in Bergen County had upheld the law last
year. The state's highest court accepted the case on direct appeal
and on Tuesday reversed that finding. Because of the litigation,
the law had never been permitted to take effect, and it now stands
nullified.
</P>
<P>
   Tasy said she was outraged by the ruling because the court
ignored public support for the measure. ''This court is completely
out of control,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the Supreme Court justices had unfairly placed
themselves in the position of lawmakers. ''That is what offends me
the most,'' he said. ''We had one goal. That was to give parents
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Poritz said that while the state government may take steps to
protect parents' rights, the parental-notification requirement
placed an excessive burden on a girl's constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''We acknowledge that the state has a substantial interest in
preserving the family and protecting the rights of parents. When
weighed against the right of a young woman to make the most
personal and intimate decision whether to carry a child to term,
however, the insubstantial connection between the notification
requirement and the interests expressed by the state is not
sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices Daniel O'Hern and Peter Verniero dissented, saying the
law did not impair free exercise of the constitutional right to
abortion. New Jersey's version of the law did not require parental
consent, only notice.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hern recently retired from the court, and Verniero, appointed
to the bench last year, was also a former attorney general in the
Whitman administration. O'Hern said the federal courts would have
approved this law.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh justice, Marie Garibaldi, had already retired when
the case was argued Jan. 19 and her replacement, Justice Jaynee
LaVecchia, had not yet been sworn in.
</P>
<P>
   Poritz said the court deliberately did not address the moral
questions posed by abortion, adding, ''At the end of the day, those
questions are left to the individual to decide for herself.''
</P>
<P>
   But Poritz made it fairly clear the court's four-member majority
will never accept a law seeking to ban abortion, citing not only
the U.S. Constitution but the state constitution, which has a
clause that protects privacy rights and equal protection of the
laws more specifically than the federal document.
</P>
<P>
   ''A young woman's right to choose, to personal dignity and
autonomy, is imbedded in the liberties found on the constitutions
of the United States and of this state,'' Poritz said.
</P>
<P>
   And even in his dissent, Verniero said he also would vote to
strike down a law ''that infringed on the reproductive rights of
women to any significant degree.'' He just did not agree this law
posed such an infringement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-16-00 0204 </TRAILER>
