<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pedro Confident Shoulder OK  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD ULMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Red Sox are in a playoff race as tight
as Pedro Martinez's shoulder. At a time when his team can't afford
to lose him, he says he doesn't expect to miss a start.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see why not,'' he said Tuesday night when asked if he
could take his regular turn in the rotation Saturday against Texas.
Then he was checked by team physician Dr. William Morgan, watched
his team lose to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays 3-1 and pronounced
himself improved.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm feeling better,'' he said after the game. ''I'm supposed
to throw (Wednesday). Hopefully, everything will go all right. ...
I'm optimistic everything is going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez pulled himself out of Monday night's 7-3 win over the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays with a stiff shoulder in the fourth inning,
his shortest start of the season. He already has had one stint on
the disabled list this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm normally pretty stubborn about staying out there but I'm
at the stage where I can't afford to go on the disabled list
again,'' he said. ''The team needs me, so I decided to play it
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The AL strikeout leader didn't have the usual pop on his
fastball. Baseball's ERA leader even gave up a three-run homer to
Miguel Cairo, who hadn't homered all season.
</P>
<P>
   And the Red Sox, who have struggled at the plate recently,
needed a grand slam by Rico Brogna in the bottom of the ninth to
pull out the victory that left them 1&AMP;frac12; games behind Oakland and
one-half game behind Cleveland in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday night's game, Martinez appeared cheerful as he
awaited an examination on his stiff right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's OK. He's a player,'' he said of the light-hitting
Cairo's homer. ''I can give them up just like anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he felt fine throwing between starts in Texas,
where Boston wrapped up a three-game series Sunday. So he was
surprised when the shoulder felt stiff as he stretched before
Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I gave one inning, two innings,'' he said. ''The third inning
it got a little tighter and then the fourth inning I couldn't even
throw the ball. So I just said, 'No, I'm coming out.' It was my
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Relievers Hipolito Pichardo, Rod Beck and Derek Lowe shut down
the Devil Rays the rest of the way, but even Boston's outstanding
bullpen can't carry the team the way Martinez can.
</P>
<P>
   He's 13-4 with a 1.59 ERA and 210 strikeouts, 62 more than
Cleveland's Bartolo Colon, who is second in the AL. Opponents'
batting average of .170 against last year's Cy Young award winner
is the lowest in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has no intention of returning to the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ''Out of the picture. Disabled list and stuff like that, missing
a start's out of the picture. Hopefully,'' he said. ''I know my
body and I know I was just stiff.''
</P>
<P>
   It's happened before.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez pitched only four innings in Game 1 of Boston's
first-round playoff series last year against Cleveland before
leaving with shoulder stiffness, but he returned to throw six
no-hit innings of relief as Boston won the decisive fifth game.
</P>
<P>
   He lasted just 3 2-3 innings on July 18, 1999, against the
Florida Marlins, allowing nine runs -- seven earned -- and 12 hits.
He went on the disabled list after that game.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, he struck out five batters in two innings
before Cairo homered in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was perfectly fine in Texas,'' he said. ''After traveling
it's so uncomfortable, pulling your bag around and, I guess,
sleeping uncomfortably I think made it worse.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Red Sox in the middle of a 10-game homestand that ends
next Wednesday, Martinez can sleep in his own bed and, he hopes,
pitch from his own mound on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
