<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Still no significant progress to resolve phone strike  </HEADLINE>
By D. IAN HOPPER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Scant progress is being reported in contract
talks to return thousands of striking phone technicians and
operators for Verizon Communications to work.
</P>
<P>
   The strike by 87,000 employees for Verizon, the nation's largest
local phone company, entered its 11th day Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   About 30,000 managers have been filling in for striking
employees. To alleviate some of the pressure on managers, several
hundreds retired workers have agreed to help out.
</P>
<P>
   Talks adjourned late Tuesday with very limited success, union
and company spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been exchanging proposals back and forth,'' said Jeff
Miller, a spokesman for the Communications Workers of America. ''So
far we cannot report a great deal of progress, but our negotiators
are in constant touch and are working hard on the major issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Both CWA and the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers
wish to scale back a provision for mandatory overtime, which can
amount to up to 15 extra hours a week. Union officials said the
clause was intended to give the company flexibility during
emergencies, but is used too liberally.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it is an answer to the tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon, the nation's largest local and wireless telephone
company, was formed from the summer merger of Bell Atlantic and
GTE.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon spokesman Eric Rabe said the company is working to
complete 80,000 to 90,000 pending repairs. He said 200 to 300
retired workers have agreed to join thousands of managers filling
in for the striking workers.
</P>
<P>
   The strike by about 87,200 members of the two unions affects
Delaware, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, New
Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Virginia,
West Virginia and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Verizon Communications: http://www.verizon.com
</P>
<P>
   Communications Workers of America: http://www.cwa-union.org
</P>
<P>
   International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers:
http://www.ibew.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
