<HEADLINE> 75 DNC Protesters Arrested  </HEADLINE>
By ANTHONY BREZNICAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Several dozen protesters were arrested
Tuesday during demonstrations on the second day of the Democratic
National Convention, mostly from an animal-rights protest and a
rolling rally by bicyclists. At least 75 people were taken into
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five people were arrested as animal rights activists
opposed to the fur trade banged on the windows of businesses,
including a fur shop.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 to 50 people were taken into custody from a bicycle
rally, but it was unclear whether they would be charged.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates and reporters leaving the convention were met by
hecklers shouting ''Shame, Shame, Shame'' and chanting anti-death
penalty slogans as they walked to shuttle buses and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know, I don't have a problem with that. I think it's
healthy,'' said Indiana state Rep. Sheila Klinker. A colleague of
hers from the state delegation disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's really ironic is that this whole convention probably
supports the protesters rights and they are infringing on our
rights,'' said Sue Wanzer, of Bloomington, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Most protests Tuesday were smaller than demonstrations Monday
that culminated in a clash between police and a crowd at a free
concert in the protest zone outside the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Police met the animal rights protesters about eight blocks from
arena, and kept the public and the media out of a two-block area
around a bank while they made arrests.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 people gathered on the periphery, clapping, banging
drums and shouting for the streets to be re-opened before police
ordered them to disperse.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were peaceful demonstrators. It was a lawful assembly. This
is an unlawful arrest,'' Geoff Kerns said as he and others were
handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   At Edward Borovay Furs, where protesters banged on the windows,
workers quickly moved to hide the shop's name by spray-painting an
awning and removing a sign.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrested were charged with conspiracy to commit a felony
based on items found in their backpacks, including flammable
liquids and small fireworks, said Cmdr. David Kalish, a police
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 bicyclists snarled downtown traffic during the
evening rush in a ''critical mass protest'' seeking more bike lanes
and other facilities for cyclists. The string of bike riders and
police trailing them stretched the length of a city block. Cyclists
wove through cars, rang bike bells and waved signs that said ''End
slavery to the oil and automobile industry.''
</P>
<P>
   After allowing them to ride around the city for more than an
hour, police detained more than 30 people near the convention
center, including an Associated Press reporter who was following
the demonstrators on a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. John Pasquariello, a police spokesman, said not all of
those detained had been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   In other events:
</P>
<P>
   -- The American Civil Liberties Union said it would sue the Los
Angeles Police Department for its treatment of the media during
Monday night's clash, accusing police of specifically targeting
reporters to keep them from doing their jobs. Police had no
immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   -- As dusk fell Tuesday, about 500 demonstrators, including gay
activists, marched from Pershing Square, a hub for protest
activity, to a cluster of government buildings about eight blocks
away. They fell silent in front of one of the buildings, leaving
only the whirring sounds of police helicopters hovering overhead.
Police eventually let the group return to the square.
</P>
<P>
   -- Demonstrators carrying dove puppets made of shredded white
cloth marched from the abandoned $170 million Belmont Learning
Center to the nearby office of Gov. Gray Davis. Some chanted,
''Schools not jails!'' The school project was abandoned after it
was learned it was being built on contaminated land.
</P>
<P>
   -- Protesters supporting unions and women's rights moved from
Pershing Square to a downtown federal building where two lines of
U.S. marshals and police in riot helmets blocked them from
entering. ''LAPD, go away! Racist, sexist, anti-gay!'' a crowd of
hundreds chanted.
</P>
</TEXT>
