<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Drops 25; Nasdaq Gains 36  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed Wednesday as investors
digested the dual effects of modest inflation brought about by a
cooling economy.
</P>
<P>
   In late morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 24.91 at 11,042.09.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 3.45 at 1,487.88, and the
Nasdaq composite index was up 35.84 at 3,887.50.
</P>
<P>
   A selloff in retail stocks helped drag down the Dow index. Home
Depot fell $3.625 to $50.124, and Wal Mart was down $2.187 to
$49.563.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sold retail stocks in the fear that second-half
profits could fall short of expectations if consumer spending eases
in step with the Federal Reserve Board's policy of cooling the
economy to fight inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Economic data released Wednesday provided further evidence that
the Fed's strategy to slow the economy may be working.
</P>
<P>
   A government report showed that consumer prices rose a mild 0.2
percent last month, as the cost of gasoline and natural gas eased
after soaring in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department's Consumer Price Index core rate, which
excludes the volatile food and energy sectors, also rose just 0.2
percent, for a fourth consecutive month, suggesting that most other
prices remain under control.
</P>
<P>
   If the Fed, which has raised interest rates six times in the
past 14 months, feels their plan is working, interest rates will
likely be left unchanged at the Fed's next meeting Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you have slowing economic growth, there are two effects.
First, there is reduced pressure for the Federal Reserve Board to
increase interest rates. However, a slower economy also creates
less robust expectations for corporate profits, especially in the
retail sector,'' said Richard Hoey, chief economist and chief
investment strategist at Dreyfus Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks pushed the Nasdaq higher. Internet portal
companies Yahoo!, up $2.625 to $134.938, and Lycos, up $2.312 to
$60.25, led the way.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 300.7 million shares,
up from Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 2.15 at 512.08.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
