<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bellow Biographer Sums Up Writer  </HEADLINE>
By HILLEL ITALIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- This fall, something highly unusual will happen
in the world of literature.
</P>
<P>
   A major biography of a celebrated writer will be published in
October. More than 600 pages, it's a deeply researched book that
took more than a decade to complete. It includes private
correspondence, interviews with friends and family members and some
highly intimate personal details.
</P>
<P>
   But those kinds of books come out all the time. What's unusual
now is that the subject, Saul Bellow, is still living.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bellow'' is James Atlas' long-awaited biography on the Nobel
Prize winner, who turned 85 in July. While the book was not
''authorized,'' Bellow did agree to let Atlas view private papers,
met frequently with him and didn't stop others from doing the same.
Atlas corresponded with all three of Bellow's sons, one of his
ex-wives and friends and fellow writers such as Martin Amis, Philip
Roth and the late Allan Bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Movie stars and politicians often live to see their stories told
in full, but the rules are more delicate with writers. They're
rarely thought of as public figures, individuals whose private
lives are accountable -- or even interesting -- to a general
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''Typically, a biography like that comes 10 years after the
author's death. You get a great, lumbering masterwork like Joseph
Blotner's book about Faulkner or Richard Ellmann's biography of
Joyce,'' said author and critic Jay Parini, who also contributed
material for Atlas' book.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's more common for a biographer to agree that the book will
come out after the subject has died, most famously with Boswell and
Dr. Johnson,'' said Richard Holmes, an award-winning biographer of
the English poet Samuel Coleridge.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would think it impossibly difficult to write a book like
that on a subject who's still living. If you're writing about the
living you run into the issues of respect and privacy. There's the
old saying from Voltaire, 'To the living you owe respect but to the
dead you owe nothing less than the truth.'''
</P>
<P>
   Atlas first contacted Bellow in 1987, when the author already
was in his 70s, but said he never considered withholding the book
until Bellow died. For a biographer, it was an ideal situation.
Atlas had cooperation from Bellow, but because they had no official
relationship Atlas could publish as he pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bellow's never been the kind of person to make arrangements.
He just lets things happen. It's very much in keeping with how he's
always lived,'' Atlas said.
</P>
<P>
   Roth was among those who suggested that Atlas write the Bellow
biography. Atlas grew up in Chicago, the setting for some of
Bellow's greatest work, and the two had some mutual acquaintances.
In addition, Atlas had previously written an acclaimed biography of
the poet Delmore Schwartz, an old friend of Bellow's and the model
for the title character of his Pulitzer Prize-winning novel,
''Humboldt's Gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlas said he did leave out some information from his new
biography, but ''Bellow'' does not read like a work that's been
softened.
</P>
<P>
   The book is both journalism and commentary. Atlas chronicles
Bellow's rise from young immigrant in Chicago to elder statesman in
the literary world. He notes the strong similarities between
Bellow's work and the author's life. He also describes a man as
complex in person as he is on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Winner of countless literary awards, Bellow hasn't always
conducted himself like a ''distinguished'' writer. He has married
five times, using his domestic life as material in such novels as
''Herzog'' and ''Humboldt's Gift.'' His comments about blacks and
women have often been criticized and he has offered more than a few
uncomplimentary remarks about fellow writers.
</P>
<P>
   Bellow is an opinionated man and Atlas has written an
opinionated book. Feminists, he writes, were ''justifiably''
offended by Bellow's presentation of women in his novels. He also
finds Bellow guilty of ''general disparagement of blacks,''
especially in the novels ''Henderson the Rain King'' and ''Mr.
Sammler's Planet.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Having an opinion is one of the cardinal requirements of
biographies,'' said Atlas, founding editor for the popular Penguin
Lives series of short biographies. ''I think one of the reasons the
Penguin books are so successful is their strong points of view. As
titillating as some of the information may be, you need some kind
of vision to bring it together.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlas both analyzes and psychoanalyzes his subject. Bellow, he
writes, ''lacked the reserves of self-esteem needed to engage in
rigorous self-criticism.'' He believes Bellow favored ''subservient
women in order to serve his own shaky self-image.'' He finds ''an
element of snobbery in Bellow's reluctance to affiliate himself
with (fellow) Jewish writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlas also assesses Bellow's sex life, citing unfavorable
comments about his performance in bed, and the observation from one
woman that Bellow ''had a biblical Old World morality, but his fly
was entirely unzipped at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellow's work is highly praised, but with reservations. Atlas
faults the author for ''a tendency in his novels to push his plots
so far that they verge on farce.'' He says that at times Bellow's
''philosophizing got in the way of his natural ebullience'' and
comments elsewhere that the author is not ''a complex thinker.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellow has long been compared to the narrators of his novels and
the man Atlas presents suggests an ideal Bellovian character, rich
in contradictions: cerebral but high-strung, boyish but
old-fashioned, attached to the past but unpredictable as a friend,
terrified of commitment yet fatally eager to marry.
</P>
<P>
   ''Conflictedness is part of the essence of human nature,'' Atlas
said. ''I didn't want to fall into the trap of antagonism; I felt a
profound emotional and biographical affinity that never flagged
during all the years I worked on this book. But on the other hand,
I certainly didn't want to write a work of hagiography.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellow now teaches at Boston University, and his assistant said
he would neither read the book nor comment on it. The author, who
threatened legal action against a previous biographer, apparently
has a morbid view of the whole genre. He once called biography ''a
specter viewed by a specter'' and labeled biographers ''the shadow
of the tombstone falling across the garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlas himself has mixed feelings. In the book's acknowledgments,
he remembers with great excitement ''the ever-widening circle of
family, friends, and associates'' of Bellow, whose life he
describes as a ''peripatetic and dazzling passage through the
world.'' But he also noted the difficulty of writing about a man he
knows so well.
</P>
<P>
   ''(I) immersed myself in his life more deeply than I ever did in
(Delmore) Schwartz's,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the earlier work, I was a historian, a chronicler, an
archivist, putting together a portrait largely from hearsay. Here,
my proximity to the life I was writing was so close (so
suffocating, Bellow might have said) that it recalled the scene in
his early novel, 'The Victim,' where Leventhal, the beleaguered
hero, is forced to carry his double, his tormentor, Allbee, on his
back.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were moments,'' Atlas added, ''when I wondered if I was
living my own life at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
