<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crenshaw Reconginzed With 'Best of'  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- After 19 years, 10 albums and countless nights
on stage, the songwriting craft of critical fave Marshall Crenshaw
was finally recognized with a ''Best Of'' collection.
</P>
<P>
   Its title: ''This is Easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw appreciates the irony, but says credit for the name
belongs to the folks at Rhino Records. And it's appropriate in one
way: Putting the collection together was easier than the career
that produced it.
</P>
<P>
   For Crenshaw, it began when the phone rang in his Brooklyn
kitchen earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was minding my own business one evening when Gary Stewart at
the label called and announced he wanted to do this,'' Crenshaw
recalls. ''I thought, 'Great. Yeah, that would be cool.'''
</P>
<P>
   And it is. ''This Is Easy: The Best of Marshall Crenshaw''
assembles some of the finest pop tunes ever recorded, from his 1981
debut Shake Records single ''Something's Gonna Happen'' through
1996's irresistibly catchy ''What Do You Dream Of?''
</P>
<P>
   The collection chronicles Crenshaw's growth as a
singer-songwriter as well as his ever-evolving musical styles.
Rhino is simultaneously re-releasing his first album, ''Marshall
Crenshaw,'' with 10 bonus tracks that include covers of Buddy
Holly's ''Rave On'' and the Parliaments' ''Look at What I Almost
Missed.'' Both albums were released this week.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that Crenshaw is most proud of -- his
commitment to making different music -- is one of the things that
caused him career woes. He's been dumped by two labels, nearly quit
recording in the late '80s, and never achieved the mainstream
success once predicted for him.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw's only hit single -- ''Till I Hear It from You'' -- was
co-written with members of the Gin Blossoms, who rode the song into
the Top 40. He's never done a version of the song himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit native first signed in 1982 with Warner Brothers,
where his first album received a rave Rolling Stone review.
</P>
<P>
   But the somewhat spare sound of album No. 1 shared little with
the Steve Lillywhite-produced thump of his second album, ''Field
Day,'' which in turn sounded nothing like the laid-back third
album, ''Downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a lot of risk-taking going on,'' Crenshaw reflects.
''The sound kind of varies from one album to the next -- a lot of
diversity in sounds and approaches. ... That's something I'm really
proud of, that I always had the nerve to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The label's response when Crenshaw delivered ''Field Day'' in
1983? ''I did catch a ton of garbage for that second album,'' he
recalled. ''I threw people a major curveball.''
</P>
<P>
   And when he followed up with ''Downtown'' in 1985? ''I guess,''
he reflects, ''further mystification.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw, in a phone interview from home, speaks in a painfully
scratchy voice: A cold complicated by a couple of weekend gigs has
laid him low. But he grows animated when talking about the first
time he sat in a studio surrounded by the tapes of his first seven
studio albums.
</P>
<P>
   ''You make a record, you pour yourself into it, and then the
tapes get carted off to a storage locker in a crater in the San
Joaquin Valley,'' he says. ''But seeing it all in one place, and
listening to it again, it's like I reclaimed it all of a sudden.''
</P>
<P>
   The process brought back memories, good and bad, from across two
decades -- his eight-year stay at Warner, his one-shot ''Life's Too
Short'' for MCA Records, his eventual landing at New York
independent label Razor &AMP; Tie.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each album has its own really vivid memories,'' Crenshaw
reflects. ''Each captures a place in time, and a certain place in
my life. I can hear echoes of what music I was listening to then,
what I was discovering or intrigued by.''
</P>
<P>
   Every album shows Crenshaw's penchant for penning incredible
hooks; the collection title track, ''This Is Easy,'' from his 1987
''Mary Jean &AMP; Nine Others,'' is a perfect example.
</P>
<P>
   The final choice of tunes on the 22-song collection belonged to
the record company, and Crenshaw acknowledges there were ''two or
three which I might have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Which ones?
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't wanna say,'' Crenshaw avers.
</P>
<P>
   He does say that plans to do music for a Disney animation
project have fallen through: ''It just kind of went away.'' He
fared better on another project, writing an original score for a
PBS documentary, ''Yogi Berra: Deja Vu All Over Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Over his career, Crenshaw has earned incessant critical kudos
and a loyal (if small) audience. So who does he expect to pick up
''This Is Easy''?
</P>
<P>
   ''The potential audience is anybody who likes rock 'n' roll,''
Crenshaw says. ''There's stuff on there that's as good as rock
music can get. I was so surprised and pleased about the way it
turned out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
