<DOCNO> APW20000816.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Out of the Red and Into the Ring  </HEADLINE>
By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLASGOW, Scotland (AP) -- How it came about could be the makings
of an opera itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish Opera, lately rescued from bankruptcy, has plunged
into a production of Richard Wagner's epic ''Ring of the
Nibelungs'' cycle, the most expensive, demanding work it could
possibly tackle.
</P>
<P>
   The company hasn't done the cycle for nearly 30 years, and the
Aug. 21 premiere will be at the renowned Edinburgh Festival, which
has never staged the work in all its 54 years.
</P>
<P>
   The four-opera cycle, running a total of 15 hours, is a saga of
gods and earthlings, giants and dwarves, treasure, a curse and the
triumph of love, based on Teutonic-Norse mythology. It can be so
endlessly interpreted that critics and addicts everywhere are keen
to know what's new in the latest production, wherever it takes
place.
</P>
<P>
   It makes news both when a producer does it traditionally --
although you are unlikely to see the horned helmets and bearskins
of Wagner's day -- or conceptually, with singers in suits, tuxedos,
evening gowns or hotpants.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Scottish company began rehearsals of
''Rhinegold,'' the first of the four-part cycle, at its Glasgow
base, to perform in the Edinburgh festival.
</P>
<P>
   The other three parts -- ''Valkyrie,'' ''Siegfried'' and
''Twilight of the Gods'' (''Gotterdammerung'') -- will be staged one
by one over the next three years, with the full cycle at the
Edinburgh festival in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The company could only start the four-year project with
financial backing from the festival and the Bank of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ''Spreading it over four years will ease the burden,'' said
Richard Armstrong, the company's music director and a renowned
Wagnerian who is in charge of the whole proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ''It must seem curious when we are stretched financially, but
the collaboration with the festival and the bank and doing it part
by part puts the scale into a different perspective,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company won't say what the production is costing, but
Armstrong raised an eyebrow when told the Seattle Opera had just
invested $10 million in a new ''Ring,'' implying his version will
cost much less.
</P>
<P>
   He said doing the ''Ring'' was the idea of Brian McMaster, the
Edinburgh Festival's director, with whom he worked for 10 years at
the Welsh National Opera. McMaster has said that Wagner's epic
stirs more excitement than any other work of art and that everyone
should have the opportunity to see it.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the arts world, art has to lead,'' Armstrong said. ''If you
wait for the money nothing would happen, although the balance sheet
must balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has assembled a singing cast of 14 from seven
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like to work with people freshly on the scene who haven't
sung their roles before,'' he said. ''The first reason is financial
-- we don't pay large international fees, but we do provide a
first-class environment for preparation which singers find very,
very important when they undertake a first-time role.
</P>
<P>
   ''Second is that my preferred way of working is to do it in
great detail in terms of how a role is sung, making the connection
between the music and drama, and that's best when grooming someone
from the start,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bass-baritone role of Wotan, ruler of the gods, has gone to
Matthew Best, a 43-year-old British conductor-singer who studied
music at Cambridge University and has sung in Europe and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's my first Wotan and is immensely demanding, like a voyage
of discovery, but I've had my eye on it for at least 10 years,''
Best said.
</P>
<P>
   He has sung other Wagnerian roles -- Kurwenal in ''Tristan and
Isolde,'' Amfortas in ''Parsifal'' and the title role in ''The
Flying Dutchman'' -- but Wotan ''is a much bigger fish altogether,''
Best said.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish Opera is Scotland's flagship arts ensemble, but it was
only 48 hours from closure in November when the Scottish government
provided emergency funding of more than $3 million to save it. That
reportedly was the 11th time since the company was founded in 1962
that it had been rescued from insolvency. It has a reputation for
artistic excellence, but has been chronically underfunded.
</P>
<P>
   Its current annual income is $16.5 million from box office and
government and local authority subsidies, along with commercial and
private sponsors. But uncertainty over next year's funding means it
hasn't been able to confirm its program for the post-Christmas
second half of the new season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I look forward to the day when it's not the money difficulties
that make the headlines but the work we do -- and the people of
Scotland are hungry for our work,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Rhinegold'' will be performed at the Edinburgh Festival
Theater Aug. 21, 23, 26 and 28, and at the Theater Royal, Glasgow,
Sept. 7, 9, 13 and 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
