<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uncovering a Bit of Broadway History  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Back in the Dark Ages, when Broadway show tunes
were still the stuff of popular music, composers such as Richard
Rodgers, Frank Loesser, Jule Styne and others would produce demo
recordings of their new musicals in hopes major artists would
record the songs.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the shows went into rehearsal, these talented
songwriters would gather a small group of singers and musicians in
a studio to get down on discs their latest efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Sent off to record company executives and the likes of Perry
Como, Tony Bennett, Frank Sinatra, Peggy Lee, Johnny Mathis and
other stars, these recordings were considered expendable sales
tools that would help sell the music to a wider audience. Most were
destroyed, but a few survived.
</P>
<P>
   Now a bit of Broadway history has been uncovered with the
release of ''Broadway First Take,'' which celebrates these original
demos by putting some of them out on compact disc.
</P>
<P>
   Volume 1, released on the Slider Music label, features demos of
songs from ''Gigi,'' ''How to Succeed in Business Without Really
Trying'' and ''Hello, Dolly!'' Volume 2, due in late September,
celebrates ''Flower Drum Song'' (with Richard Rodgers himself at
the piano), ''Promises, Promises'' (including three songs cut from
the show) and ''La Cage aux folles.'' More volumes are to come.
</P>
<P>
   Showcased on these discs is a select group of singers, unknown
outside the business, but accomplished artists in their own right.
And in the center, with most of the choice female solos and duets,
is a distinctive singer named Rose Marie Jun.
</P>
<P>
   From the late 1950s into the 1980s, Jun made more than 70 demos.
From hits like ''West Side Story'' and ''The Sound of Music'' to
forgotten flops like ''Copper and Brass'' and the prophetically
named ''Nowhere to Go But Up,'' she sang much of what Broadway had
to offer -- usually before anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Today, sitting in an Upper West Side apartment she shares with a
solid, sweet-faced gray cat named Molly, Jun is almost apologetic
about her unique place in musical theater.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't the business I set out to be in,'' says Jun, who
came here from Cedar Rapids, Iowa, in the 1950s after studying
classical music at Coe College in Cedar Rapids, the University of
Michigan and the Opera House in Rome. ''I came here thinking to set
the world on fire and just somehow didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   She did just fine, though, doing jingles on radio and
television. Her first? Singing a jingle for Nestea -- in Yiddish.
But from Chiquita banana to Winston cigarettes to ''Wouldn't you
really rather have a Buick?'' -- she paid the rent. Other studio
work, plus appearances on Perry Como's television show helped, too.
</P>
<P>
   Jingles opened doors at Chappell Music, the big music publishing
company. From Chappell, Jun got an introduction to Richard Rodgers
and other composers who were looking for singers to do demos of
their new theater scores.
</P>
<P>
   If the commercials were done in big studios with full
orchestras, Jun recalls, the theater demos more often were not.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just a trio or maybe a quartet was used because the composers
wanted the songs to stand on their own -- to be heard without all
the trappings you put on songs when you really record them,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Jun was not a highly stylized singer, a quality composers liked.
Plus she was a quick study.
</P>
<P>
   ''I could read music really fast and didn't waste an entire day
doing take after take after take. If you did two or three takes
that already was too much for these recordings,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a big range at the time. I had been a lyric soprano when
I was studying, but I had this chest register, too, that sounded
pop. So I could do anything they wanted me to do,'' she adds. She
sits surrounded by a room filled with memories of music. There are
photos of her with such legends as Sinatra and Como, a piano, of
course, and a lot of phonograph records and sheet music against one
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Often Jun was there at the birth of a major hit -- ''How to
Succeed,'' ''A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum,''
''Hello, Dolly!''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we realized it at the time. We were kids. And
some of the composers were, too. Jerry Herman was still a kid,''
she explains.
</P>
<P>
   ''They didn't always know what they exactly wanted either. So
they would say, 'Well, what do you think?' And we would work out
something and if they liked it, fine, go ahead and do it ... if
they didn't like it, they would say, 'No, I don't think so.'''
</P>
<P>
   The established masters were more particular.
</P>
<P>
   ''When Richard Rodgers showed you the music, you had to sing it
exactly the way he wrote it. No leeway. But he was usually right.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jule Styne was tough and very much a stickler for how he
wanted things done. He was a great piano player and could play
anything, in any key.
</P>
<P>
   ''Others, like Jerry Herman, gave you a lot more freedom to
interpret, if you could. Some of them kind of liked that because
this was one of the first times they had heard their own stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet connections with these great men didn't get Jun roles in
their shows.
</P>
<P>
   ''They seemed to draw a line between having us do these demos
and appearing on stage,'' she says. ''It was very strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she ever would have said yes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not a stage performer and never really pretended to be.
Besides I get terrible stage fright. I think I would have been very
nervous on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet she did one show -- ''Peg,'' Peggy Lee's short-lived
autobiographical musical in 1983. Jun appeared on stage with a
group of singers and a band. It ran five performances.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you come down to it, I had a pretty good niche as a
studio singer,'' she says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
