<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of Aug.
20-26:
<TEXT>
<P>
   70 years ago: Greta Garbo starred in ''Romance.'' She wore a
Gilbert Adrian hat tilted down over one eye in the film, helping to
set a fashion trend.
</P>
<P>
   65 years ago: The Benny Goodman Orchestra played a concert that
is now considered to be the start of the Swing Era. The concert was
performed in a ballroom in Los Angeles. It included the song ''Just
You, Just Me.''
</P>
<P>
   40 years ago: Connie Francis made her acting debut when filming
began on the movie ''Where the Boys Are.''
</P>
<P>
   And Stevie Wonder reached No. 1 on the pop and R&AMP;B charts with
''Fingertips, Part Two'' and No. 1 on the album chart with ''The
12-Year-Old Genius.''
</P>
<P>
   35 years ago: Sandra Dee, the last major star under exclusive
contract to a large studio, ended that relationship with
Universal-International when filming was completed on ''A Man Could
Get Killed.''
</P>
<P>
   30 years ago: Jimi Hendrix played at the Isle of Wight Pop
Festival off the coast of England. He died in London three weeks
later.
</P>
<P>
   And Lou Reed left the Velvet Underground, the group he formed
with John Cale in 1964. The group's last performance, which was in
New York, was later released as an album, ''Live at Max's Kansas
City.''
</P>
<P>
   25 years ago: The Average White Band, most of whom were
Scottish, topped the R&AMP;B chart in the United States with ''Cut the
Cake.''
</P>
<P>
   And the long-running Broadway musical ''42nd Street'' opened.
After the performance, it was announced that director Gower
Champion had died earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   15 years ago: The blue suede boots that Carl Perkins wore during
stage appearances were stolen from his tour bus while he was in
Memphis, Tenn., for a concert. The song ''Blue Suede Shoes,'' which
Perkins wrote in 1955, helped make him a recording star.
</P>
<P>
   And Bruce Springsteen gave $25,000 to the Community Food Bank,
based in Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   10 years ago: Irish singer-songwriter Sinead O'Connor banned the
playing of the American national anthem at her show in Holmdel,
N.J. In turn, some radio stations refused to play her music.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Danson, star of the hit sitcom ''Cheers,'' was late for an
appearance at an American Oceans Campaign benefit in Dana Point,
Calif., because a truckload of tuna overturned on the freeway,
backing up traffic for miles. Danson was president and co-founder
of the organization, dedicated to the protection and restoration of
the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   And the British Academy of Film and Television Arts announced
that an award for ''outstanding contribution to world cinema''
would be presented to actor Sean Connery.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago: Another founding member of Oasis quit, the second
to leave in as many weeks. The departure of bassist Paul ''Guigsy''
McGuigan followed that of guitarist Paul ''Bonehead'' Arthurs.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken 10 years ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''What really ruined pop music is the architecture that it's
presented in. Any place that's bigger than 11,000 is just not a
suitable environment for music.'' -- Singer-songwriter Linda
Ronstadt.
</P>
</TEXT>
