<HEADLINE> Iraqi Weapons Issue Under Wraps  </HEADLINE>
by 
V0880-----
r i *1107AP-US-Iraq     08-16 0753
*1107 AP-US-Iraq,0753   
Iraqi Weapons Issue Under Wraps   
An AP News Analysis
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration's policy toward
Iraq has taken on a hush-hush quality these days. While Iraq
remains a high priority, the administration seems to think the less
said about the country's weapons programs, the better.
</P>
<P>
   The United States once was all too willing to let the world know
how menacing it thought Iraqi President Saddam Hussein was.
</P>
<P>
   Early in President Clinton's second term, after Saddam expelled
U.N. inspectors, Clinton said: ''It is essential that those
inspectors go back to work. The safety of the children of the world
depends upon it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the weapons inspectors have not been allowed in Iraq for 20
months and the Iraqis are saying they will not cooperate with a
revised inspection program that should be ready in the next two to
three weeks. None of this has elicited a stern U.S. response,
although officials say the issue is getting a lot of attention
behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   When Iraq last refused to allow the inspectors' return, in
December 1998, the United States and Britain bombed military sites
in Iraq for three days to punish Saddam for his defiance.
</P>
<P>
   What the Iraqis have been up to since is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The administration will not say to what extent the Iraqis have
been trying to reconstitute weapons of mass destruction. Many of
these armaments were destroyed by the 1998 bombings or by U.N.
sleuths who for seven years sought out the forbidden weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is ready to talk about Iraqi human rights
violations, or the 600 Kuwaiti prisoners Iraq took during the
1990-91 Gulf crisis and has refused to release, or the numerous
palaces Saddam has built for himself despite widespread deprivation
of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also contends Iraqi ''obstructionism'' has
prevented the Iraqis from reaping the full benefit of a
U.N.-sponsored humanitarian aid program.
</P>
<P>
   State Department briefers discussed Iraq for an hour on Aug. 2,
the 10th anniversary of the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait, without
mentioning the administration's thinking about the status of Iraq's
military arsenal since Saddam banished the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's rationale seems to be that public
discussion could produce demands for a tough response. By avoiding
the subject, the administration is able to keep its options open,
no small consideration in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is no international consensus for renewing
military hostilities against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   France, China and Russia, all permanent members of the U.N.
Security Council, are opposed. In December, none supported the
replacement of UNSCOM, the previous U.N. inspection system. But
rather than veto, all three abstained, so the revised inspection
program will begin with a weak international mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also are divided over what Saddam has been doing.
</P>
<P>
   ''So you thought Saddam Hussein was out of your life?''
Australian Richard Butler, a former UNSCOM chairman, asked in an
opinion piece last month. ''Sorry -- he's back, manufacturing
weapons of mass destruction.'' Butler says Saddam is a global
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Rolf Ekeus, a Swede who preceded Butler at UNSCOM, is more
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say that we felt that in all areas we have eliminated
Iraq's capabilities fundamentally,'' Ekeus said in a May speech.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than have U.N. inspectors try to track down whatever
weapons remain, Ekeus believes the focus should be on preventing
Iraq from engaging in a new weapons buildup.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Blix, the Swede picked to head the new U.N. inspection
program, told Arms Control Today magazine that he did not believe
Iraq has been trying to rearm.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis themselves appear unchastened by the pounding they
took from the U.S.-led coalition that liberated Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Jumhouriya, an Iraqi daily that speaks for the regime, said
recently that Kuwait was directly responsible for the continuing
U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any one who kills any Iraqi should not sleep, let alone those
(the Kuwaiti rulers) who have killed more than 1 million Iraqi
children and adults,'' the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for The
Associated Press since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/nea/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Library of Congress country notes:
http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/cshome.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
