<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Requests Submarine Rescue Aid  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY RENFREW
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia asked for help from the West on Wednesday
as its own rescuers desperately struggled through swirling sand and
strong currents, trying to reach 116 sailors trapped in a crippled
Russian nuclear submarine on the sea bottom.
</P>
<P>
   After days of frustrated attempts to lower a rescue capsule to
the submarine, Russia, which had refused foreign help, relented and
turned to Britain and Norway, the countries' foreign ministries
said.
</P>
<P>
   Britain had already flown a mini-submarine to Norway in
preparation to assist in a rescue effort. Norway sent a ship with
around a dozen civilian divers, but it could take up to two days to
get to the site of the submarine, the Norwegian foreign ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no sign of life from the submarine, the Kursk,
since Saturday. Russian rescuers trying to lower the capsule have
had to battle worsening weather in the Barents Sea and high winds
and waves that buffeted rescue ships, said navy Capt. Igor Babenko.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to latch on to one of the cargo hatches of the
submarine were being frustrated because the current was rocking the
capsule, making it difficult to steer, Babenko said. Rescuers were
only able to see a few inches through the muddy water even though
they had searchlights, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the submarine is lying at a sharp angle, making any
latching operation more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   A rescue capsule was almost lost during an earlier attempt
because of the strong currents, said navy spokesman Igor Dygalo,
who gave no details.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov said Wednesday there was no
sign of life aboard the submarine, but that this did not mean that
there were no survivors.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin said the situation was critical, and
everything was being done to try to reach the Kursk. In a telephone
conversation with Putin on Wednesday, President Clinton renewed
U.S. offers for help, said David Stockwell, a spokesman for the
National Security Council. There was no indication Putin asked for
help.
</P>
<P>
   The British LR5 mini-submarine was flown to Vaernes Airport near
Trondheim, Norway, is operated by a three-person crew and is
capable of holding 16 passengers. It has enough life support to
allow crew members to stay submerged for 4&AMP;frac12; days.
</P>
<P>
   The mini-submarine may be able to connect to the Kursk's hatch
via a ring on the underside of the LR5's casing, but it was not
known whether its hatches would be compatible with the Russian
vessel.
</P>
<P>
   The submarine suffered extensive damage after an explosion in
the torpedo compartment at the front of the vessel, but the cause
was not clear, the navy said. The submarine's conning tower was
damaged and protective covers of two missile tubes on the vessel's
right side were missing, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials told The Associated Press on Wednesday that the
Kursk went missing Saturday, despite official statements that it
was lost Sunday. The alarm was sounded after the Kursk failed to
make a scheduled radio contact Saturday and it was found Sunday,
said the officials, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Navy submarine monitoring Russian naval exercises in the
area heard an explosion Saturday that appeared linked to the Kursk,
U.S. officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest rescue attempt involved a larger, more powerful
capsule called the Bester, and it was hoped it would be able to
better handle the swift currents on the sea floor, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller rescue capsule that tried four times during the night
to reach the submarine was forced back to the surface after running
out of oxygen, navy officials said. Its batteries were being
recharged and the two capsules would work in turns, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the navy, Adm. Vladimir Kuroyedov, said Wednesday
that he was more confident about the chances of success and said
rescue operations would continue until at least Friday. He had
earlier warned that air in the vessel was expected to run out
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now I am feeling more confidence that the operation to rescue
the Kursk's crew will yield a result,'' he told the ITAR-Tass news
agency.
</P>
<P>
   But Kuroyedov said nothing had been heard from inside the Kursk
despite earlier reports of sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is necessary to take account of the psychology of
submariners -- when they know that rescue capsules are hovering
above them, they keep silent,'' he was quoted as saying by
ITAR-Tass.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the capsules successfully dock with the sub and sailors
can enter it and find survivors, the craft can hold only 20 people
at a time. Officials say bringing it to the surface could take up
to seven hours, a slow rise required to prevent the potentially
crippling or fatal decompression sickness.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers could also try to raise the submarine using giant
pontoons, Kuroyedov said -- a seemingly impossible prospect because
the flooded craft weighs some 20,000 tons. Another proposal called
for raising the submarine to a vertical position so part of it
protruded from the water.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the Kursk's two nuclear reactors had been
switched off and it was not carrying nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Russian nuclear submarines have been involved in a string of
accidents in recent decades. The Navy, like the rest of the Russian
military, is desperately short of money and performs almost no
maintenance on its ships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-16-00 1430 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
