<HEADLINE> Seven Killed in Kashmir Violence  </HEADLINE>
By QAISER MIRZA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India (AP) -- Indian artillery killed four people in
the Pakistani-held part of Kashmir, Pakistan said Wednesday, while
three Kashmiri militants died in a gunfight with Indian police
during violence on India's independence day.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani army said Indian shells rained down on the
Pakistani-held sector of Kashmir Tuesday, killing four people and
injuring eight others. Indian shells destroyed 10 houses and
damaged two mosques, Pakistani officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Indian-held Kashmir, three militants died in different
shootouts Tuesday night in the frontier town of Kupwara, 55 miles
north of Srinagar, Indian police said. Shells from the Pakistani
side injured a girl and damaged a house in Uri sector on the Indian
side.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir is divided between India and Pakistan, both of which
claim it in its entirety. The province is the seat of an Islamic
insurgency that has left 25,000 people dead in the past 11 years.
Islamic militants want independence for Kashmir or its unification
with Muslim Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Kashmiri militants hurled a grenade at a security
patrol in Bijbehara town, 20 miles south of Srinagar, Indian police
said. The grenade exploded in the busy market area nearby, injuring
12 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   India celebrated its the 53rd anniversary of independence from
Britain on Tuesday, a day after Pakistan held its own celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   The disputed Kashmir region has been the flashpoint of two wars
between Pakistan and India. There is concern that another
confrontation could result in the use of nuclear weapons, which
both sides have tested.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, separatists in another part of India, the
northeastern state of Meghalaya, killed a policeman and injured two
others Tuesday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police chief B.K. Dey Sawian blamed militants from the
Hyntteriep National Liberation Council. Federal troops enforced a
curfew in the capital, Shillong, Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   India's northeast, which has been rocked by violence for more
than half a century, is home to more than 200 ethnic groups. Many
of them accuse the federal government of exploiting the region's
resources while neglecting the local economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
