<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 48; Nasdaq Gains 20  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed Wednesday as investors
digested the dual effects of modest inflation brought about by a
cooling economy.
</P>
<P>
   In midafternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 48.35 at 11,018.65. Broader stock indicators were
mixed.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 2.52 at 1,481.91, and
the Nasdaq composite index was up 19.46 at 3,871.12
</P>
<P>
   A selloff in retail stocks helped drag down the Dow index. Home
Depot fell $3.562 to $50.188, and Wal-Mart Stores was down $2.062
to $49.688.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sold retail stocks in the fear that second-half
profits could fall short of expectations if consumer spending eases
in step with the Federal Reserve Board's policy of cooling the
economy to fight inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Economic data released Wednesday provided further evidence that
the Fed's strategy to slow the economy may be working.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you have slowing economic growth, there are two effects.
First, there is reduced pressure for the Federal Reserve Board to
increase interest rates,'' said Richard Hoey, chief economist and
chief investment strategist at Dreyfus Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, a slower economy also creates less robust
expectations for corporate profits, especially in the retail
sector,'' Hoey said.
</P>
<P>
   A government report showed that consumer prices rose a mild 0.2
percent last month, as the cost of gasoline eased after soaring in
June.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department's Consumer Price Index core rate, which
excludes the volatile food and energy sectors, also rose just 0.2
percent, for a fourth consecutive month, suggesting that most other
prices remain under control.
</P>
<P>
   In another that the economy is cooling, the Commerce Department
reported Wednesday that housing construction fell 3.3 percent in
July to the lowest level in at least two years. It was the third
straight monthly decline.
</P>
<P>
   If the Fed, which has raised interest rates six times in the
past 14 months, feels their economic tightening plan is working,
interest rates will likely be left unchanged at the Fed's next
meeting Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks pushed the Nasdaq higher. Internet portal
companies Yahoo!, up $3.187 to $135.50, and Lycos, up $2.875 to
$60.813, led the way.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 627.46 million
shares, up from Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.69 at 511.62.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
