<HEADLINE> Relief Flights Resume to Sudan  </HEADLINE>
By MOHAMED OSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) -- Two planes took off Wednesday to drop
food to war-torn southern Sudan, ending an eight-day suspension of
the U.N.-sponsored aid flights.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. deputy spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva said in New York
on Tuesday that the United Nations had resumed the flights after
receiving guarantees from Sudan that the aid workers would be safe.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very pleased that we have been able to resume relief
flights in full agreement with the government,'' Masood Hyder,
acting U.N. humanitarian coordinator for Sudan, told The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-sponsored relief flights by Operation Lifeline Sudan were
suspended because of bombings of relief agency compounds, which
rebels blame on the government. Sudanese officials deny the
accusation.
</P>
<P>
   One flight took off from El Obeid, 500 miles west of Khartoum
and another from Lokichokio, Kenya, near the Sudanese border.
</P>
<P>
   The planes carried food for both government- and rebel-held
areas in the south, according to the U.N. office in Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
   The Sudanese government has accused relief organizations in the
south of giving military assistance to the Sudan People's
Liberation Army, which has fought since 1983 for autonomy for the
largely Christian and animist south. Sudan's north is predominantly
Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2 million people have died in Sudan's war and related
famines.
</P>
</TEXT>
