<HEADLINE> Chechen Official's Home Fired Upon  </HEADLINE>
By LYOMA TURPALOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- A rebel mine exploded under a Russian jeep
and armored personnel carrier in the Chechen capital Wednesday,
underlining the insurgents' capacity to mount attacks in
Russian-held territory.
</P>
<P>
   The blast, which injured one soldier, occurred near a telephone
station, where many people had gathered to make calls. After the
explosion, Russian soldiers opened fire, hitting a civilian woman
of about 18. Her wounds appeared severe.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels also fired at the home of a candidate for Russia's
parliament from Chechnya, military officials said Wednesday, days
ahead of the vote in the warring republic.
</P>
<P>
   No casualties were reported in the overnight attack on the house
of Ibragim Huseinov, who is also mayor of the town of Meskety in
eastern Chechnya, said an official with the Russian administration
in Chechnya. The gunmen escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a remote-controlled mine hit the home of the mayor of
nearby Alleroi overnight, the official said on condition of
anonymity. No casualties were reported. Alleroi and Meskety are
near the border with the Russian republic of Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks came after Russia's Interior Minister Vladimir
Rushailo and the chief of Russia's electoral commission flew to
Chechnya on Tuesday to oversee final preparations for the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rushailo said rebels were planning attacks timed to the
election, which is set for Aug. 20. Early voting has started in
some areas, including those where Russian troops are based.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will choose among 13 candidates to fill one seat in
Russia's 450-member lower house of parliament, the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
   Parliamentary elections took place in the rest of Russia last
December, when federal forces and rebels were engaged in fierce
fighting. Even though Russia still doesn't control all of Chechnya,
officials had promised that a legislator would be elected this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Security has been tightened ahead of the vote, with extra troops
sent to checkpoints and polling places. Yet federal forces have
been unable to keep small groups of rebels from sneaking into areas
the Russian forces claim to control and planting mines or staging
ambushes.
</P>
<P>
   A truck carrying servicemen was attacked on the outskirts of the
capital, Grozny, overnight, and at least three soldiers were
wounded, the administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops withdrew from Chechnya in defeat at the end of a
1994-96 war, then moved back in last September to end Chechnya's de
facto independence. The campaign came after a series of
cross-border raids by Islamic militants based in Chechnya last
August and subsequent bombings in Russia that Moscow blamed on the
rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-16-00 1537 </TRAILER>
