<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Reformists Oust Hard-Liner  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Reformist lawmakers ousted a hard-line
legislator Wednesday and made public a threat by a vigilante group
to put a bullet into the ''traitorous heads'' of those seeking
change.
</P>
<P>
   The two moves showed a new resolve by the reformers in their
struggle with conservatives led by Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who has
the last say in all state matters.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad Shirzad, a reformist legislator from southern city of
Isfahan, told the Majlis, or parliament, that a vigilante group --
claiming to be supporters of Khamenei -- had issued a statement
threatening reformists.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the bullet is not already in your traitorous heads, it is
only because of the (restraint) ordered by the supreme leader,''
said the statement read by Shirzad and broadcast live on Tehran
radio.
</P>
<P>
   The reformists in parliament showed their strength Wednesday by
voting to oust Mottahar Kazemi, a cleric and Islamic hard-liner.
</P>
<P>
   Kazemi had been appointed to his seat after the Guardian Council
canceled the election of a pro-reform candidate. The Guardian
Council, which oversees elections and other legislative matters, is
controlled by hard-liners.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 238 lawmakers at Wednesday's session, 138 voted to expel
Kazemi. Each lawmaker must be endorsed by more than half of his
peers before he can take a seat in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The seat will be decided in a new runoff vote; no date has been
set for the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The reformists suffered a setback earlier this month when
Khamenei ordered a halt to debate in parliament on easing a harsh
press law that the hard-line judiciary has used to close more than
20 pro-reform newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   But the reformers, who support President Mohammad Khatami's
campaign for liberalization, presented a new bill on Tuesday aimed
at blocking the judiciary from closing reformist newspapers --
another sign of the reformers new willingness to confront their
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The reform movement aims to end the strict Islamic rules that
govern the day-to-day lives of Iranians. The hard-liners oppose
open debates that target the foundations of their rule.
</P>
<P>
   The reformers won control of the Majlis from hard-liners in
February elections for the first time since the 1979 Islamic
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   But conservatives cling to power, using the judiciary to close
newspapers and arrest prominent reformists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-16-00 1545 </TRAILER>
