<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health official sees no quick end to West Nile virus  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOCKPORT, N.Y. (AP) - One health official said spraying to kill
mosquitoes might help a little in controlling the spread of the
West Nile virus, but predicted the virus would be a problem for
many years.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we spray we're not going to eradicate anything,'' Niagara
County Public Health Director David Wertman told the County
Legislature Tuesday. ''We're reducing the risk ... (The virus) will
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Wertman said even winter's cold weather would not put an end to
the spread, since mosquitoes spend the winter in sheltered places,
like sewers, and would take the virus with them when they re-emerge
next year.
</P>
<P>
   One crow in North Tonawanda has been confirmed to have died from
the virus, which is transmitted to humans through mosquitoes.
County Environmental Health Director James Devald said test results
were pending on 35 other dead birds from elsewhere in the county.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile symptoms include high fever, gastrointestinal
problems, muscle ache, headache and mental confusion. In the most
serious instances - usually among children, the elderly, or others
with weaker immune systems - the virus can cause a deadly swelling
of the brain known as encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   Wertman said the county does not have the equipment for aerial
spraying but could consider ground spraying if adjoining Erie
County also sprayed.
</P>
<P>
   ''There would have to be a concurrence between Erie and
Niagara,'' he said. ''We'd have to feel the benefits outweigh the
risks.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the public would be notified 24 hours before spraying,
which would be done at night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
