<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commission says Verizon rates will be cut more than expected  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Verizon New York must reduce its rates for
residential and business customers by $50 million starting Sept. 1,
not the $25 million the company formerly known as Bell Atlantic-New
York had been directed to in 1995 by the state Public Service
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the additional reductions - $22.7 million - is
coming as the result of a ruling this summer by the state's highest
court that the former Bell Atlantic's customers should share in the
profits of the sale of Bell Communications Research. The PSC had
ruled that the ratepayers should benefit by the sale because for
years they had been charged for the Bell laboratory's operations.
</P>
<P>
   The PSC said the benefits of the sale would become a permanent
reduction in Verizon's rate base and not be given consumers as a
one-time credit.
</P>
<P>
   The savings to customers under the PSC's order will amount to
about 44 cents per line per month, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Under a schedule decreed by the PSC in 1995, Verizon was already
bound to reduce rates by $25 million starting next month. That was
part of a plan to deregulate the state's telephone industry, giving
other companies access to Bell Atlantic's local customers and Bell
Atlantic the right to become an interstate, long distance carrier.
</P>
</TEXT>
