<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court upholds 30-year sentence  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A federal appeals court on Wednesday upheld the
30-year prison term given the white police officer who claimed he
was driven by ''animal rage'' to sodomize a black prisoner with a
broken broomstick.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
also said it had ''no particular reason'' to believe former police
officer Justin Volpe when he said a fellow officer, Charles
Schwarz, was not with him during the assault. Schwarz denies he was
involved and has appealed his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 9, 1997, attack occurred in a Brooklyn police station
bathroom. Volpe had arrested Abner Louima when he mistook him for
someone who punched his head as police broke up an unruly crowd
outside a nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe pleaded guilty in May 1999 to conspiracy to deprive a
person of his civil rights, deprivation of civil rights and witness
tampering. He was sentenced to 30 years in prison and ordered to
pay $281,000 in restitution.
</P>
<P>
   On appeal, Volpe's lawyers argued that Judge Eugene Nickerson in
Brooklyn unfairly penalized his client multiple times for the same
offenses and failed to credit him for naming the other officer in
the bathroom during the attack.
</P>
<P>
   They also said he should be given a lesser sentence because he
pleaded guilty, accepting responsibility for the attack on the
handcuffed Louima in one of the worst police scandals in city
history.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals panel noted that his plea came late in the
trial, after he had forced prosecutors to show most of its
extensive case against him.
</P>
<P>
   It recalled that Nickerson had concluded that Volpe showed a
lack of remorse and a failure to accept fully the wrongfulness of
his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both before and during the trial,'' the appeals court said,
''Volpe advanced the theory that Louima had sustained his injuries
during a consensual sexual encounter with another man.''
</P>
<P>
   At trials in Brooklyn, other police officers had testified that
Volpe waved around a feces-covered stick and even boasted that he
''broke a man down.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with a defense psychologist, Volpe denied ever
bragging about the assault.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no sense of accomplishment - nothing like that,'' he
said. ''It was like an animal rage.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel declined to give Volpe credit for saying
Officer Thomas Wiese - not Schwarz - was in the bathroom with him
at the time of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see no particular reason to believe Volpe was being
truthful in naming Wiese as his co-assailant in the bathroom,'' the
judges wrote.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that the assertion was never tested by
cross-examination, Schwarz did not call him as a witness and the
jury ultimately decided to convict only Schwarz, not Wiese, of
assisting Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz was sentenced in June to 15&AMP;frac12; years for his role in the
attack. Wiese received a five-year sentence for lying to the FBI
about Schwarz's role. In all, four officers have been convicted in
three trials and two have pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's lawyers have said they had hoped to shave half of
Volpe's prison term with appeal judgments.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Kornberg, one lawyer, said a further appeal was certain
but it had not been decided whether to ask the full appeals court
to hear the arguments or to seek relief from Nickerson or the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to do everything within our power to see to
it that the sentence of Mr. Volpe is reduced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Alan Vinegrad said prosecutors were very
happy with the appeals court ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-16-00 1621 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000816.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
