<HEADLINE> State maintaining vigil over dams in flooded region  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos XNR101-102
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPARTA, N.J. (AP) - Five earthen dams in Sparta remained under
scrutiny Wednesday, several days after four similar dams in the
region broke under the strain of elevated lake levels.
</P>
<P>
   A State police helicopter ferried inspectors from the Army Corps
of Engineers and the state Department of Environmental Protection
over the five on Tuesday, and expect to do so daily until water
levels recede, said Trooper Sgt. Al Della Fave.
</P>
<P>
   Of greatest concern was the Morris Lake dam, classified by state
and federal regulators as a ''high hazard,'' meaning that failure
poses the greatest risk to life and property.
</P>
<P>
   Also under watch on Wednesday were dams at Arapaho Lake, Glen
Lake, Saginaw Lake and Sunset Lake.
</P>
<P>
   By midday Wednesday, ''No new problems have arisen,'' Della Fave
said.
</P>
<P>
   The dam on Seneca Lake in Sparta burst over the weekend,
emptying it and leaving a 25-acre patch of mud. Its contents flowed
in Lake Tomahawk in Byram, bursting its dam.
</P>
<P>
   Other dams that have failed include those at Edison Pond in
Sparta and Furnace Pond in Stanhope, state officials said. Dams at
Hawthorne Lake in Sparta and at the Musconetcong River in Stanhope
were damaged, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1991 state inspection of Seneca Lake dam determined it needed
repairs, which were not done by its private owners, state officials
told The New York Times in Wednesday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   The 140-member Seneca Lake Association does not know who would
pay for repairs or whether the lake can be restored, a member of
the association's board, Tammy Crimando, told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just hoping it can be fixed, but there's a dispute about
who owns the lake, and there's a matter of determining who is
responsible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Crimando could not be immediately be reached on Wednesday. No
home listing could be found for her.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marge S. Roukema, R-Ridgewood, who represents part of the
area, said she would seek federal aid for lake owners.
</P>
<P>
   Many private lakes were built in the early 1900s by developers
seeking to offer beachfront property. Their owners are responsible
for hiring inspectors, John H. Moyle, chief of the DEP's dam safety
section, told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation since then makes it virtually impossible to build
private dams, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   The DEP had no immediate response Wednesday to a request to
interview Moyle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
