<HEADLINE> West Point Cadet Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. (AP) -- A second West Point cadet has been
sentenced to prison for breaking into a store at the academy and
stealing nearly $25,000 worth of merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   William L. Bender, 20, was sentenced to 15 months at Fort
Leavenworth, Kan., dismissed from the Army and stripped of all pay
and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't stop this feeling of eternal shame,'' Bender said as
he sobbed during Tuesday's sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Capt. Lisa Vigna, said the break-in has been a
blemish on West Point, where cadets get 19 hours of instruction in
the bedrock honor code that says they don't lie, cheat or steal or
tolerate those who do.
</P>
<P>
   Bender's lawyers argued that severe depression caused by earlier
discipline made him break into the department store Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal with prosecutors, Bender pleaded guilty to smashing a
window in the store with Cadet John B. Taylor IV. They filled
several duffel bags with watches, leather jackets, video cameras
and jewelry valued at about $24,821.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was sentenced to 18 months in June.
</P>
