<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Who will be NYPD's next top cop? AP Photos </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - It's the biggest guessing game - at least within
the confines of Police Headquarters and City Hall - since ''Who
shot J.R.?'' Who will Mayor Rudolph Giuliani name to succeed Howard
Safir as the city's police commissioner?
</P>
<P>
   Three names have emerged as contenders: Chief of Department
Joseph Dunne; Corrections Commissioner Bernard Kerik; and Dennison
Young Jr., a close friend of Giuliani's for more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   All three men are deemed good choices, but all have flaws as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors abound that Dunne, 52, is the leading candidate. He is
the highest ranking uniformed officer in the NYPD, having worked
his way up from his days on the beat. The 30-year veteran is
well-liked and respected among the rank-and-file and is known for
having a rapport with minority groups, something the Safir
administration lacked.
</P>
<P>
   But Dunne has not known Giuliani long, and his longevity in the
department may suggest more loyalty to his officers than to the
mayor, said two police sources who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ''He hasn't proved his loyalty to the mayor yet,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   But Dunne apparently won over Safir, who appointed him chief of
department last year. Safir, a longtime friend of Giuliani's, has
reportedly recommended that Dunne replace him after Safir leaves to
take a job in a private firm.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik, 44, has known Giuliani for a long time and has been
praised by the mayor for work at the Corrections Department
reducing violence among inmates. He's a former cop, having served
as an NYPD narcotics detective for most of his eight years on the
force.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik's only roadblock is that he does not have a college
degree, a prerequisite to being police commissioner. He would have
to get a waiver from City Hall to bypass the requirement. A high
school dropout with an equivalency diploma, Kerik has been taking
courses through Empire State College and needs 24 more credits for
his bachelor's degree.
</P>
<P>
   Young's long relationship with the mayor could be his greatest
asset. Currently Giuliani's counsel, he is considered by City Hall
insiders to be one of the mayor's closest advisers. The 56-year-old
has been Giuliani's point person with the NYPD since the mayor took
office in 1994, and knows the department's inner workings
intimately.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you look at the candidates, there's really no one more
qualified than Denny Young and no one that would have that instant
comfort level with the mayor,'' said an ex-police official
knowledgeable about the department and who spoke on the condition
of anonymity
</P>
<P>
   But Young is not a police officer, which could rankle cops who
never warmed to Safir, a longtime federal official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
