<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transportation watchdog group calls for governor to expand truck ban </HEADLINE>
By LORI HINNANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A transportation watchdog group Wednesday
called on the state to strengthen a law that bans big rigs from
local roads by allowing municipal police to enforce the law and by
expanding the types of trucks included under it.
</P>
<P>
   The Tri-State Transportation Group, a New York-based coalition
of various activist organizations, held a news conference that
featured mayors of several New Jersey towns, as well as victims of
accidents involving tractor-trailers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law enacted last year, only state troopers are
permitted to stop trucks, inspect them for various violations and
cite them. Members of the watchdog group said local police also had
been allowed to inspect trucks until 1993, when State Police took
over the work entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ''Local police did it in the past; they can do it again,'' said
Les Hamilton, mayor of East Amwell.
</P>
<P>
   State Police spokesman John Hagerty said the agency assumed sole
responsibility for truck inspections to accommodate federal rules
passed at that time.
</P>
<P>
   He said the federal rules were passed ''so that interstate
commerce would not be hampered by unwarranted stops by police
agencies throughout a state.'' If multiple agencies were allowed to
conduct the inspections, Hagerty said, ''the truck would never get
through a state.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Clancy, 29, of Lambertville, said her car was struck
head-on last year on Route 31 in East Amwell after a trucker lost
control of the vehicle and careened into her. She said she is still
undergoing treatment for injuries she suffered in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tractor-trailers are not meant to be on local roads,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Stegman witnessed a May tractor-trailer accident that
ended when the runaway truck slammed into a Lambertville video
store, killing the clerk inside.
</P>
<P>
   Stegman said in many cases, local police know better than state
troopers whether a vehicle belongs on their roads.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know our roads,'' he said. ''We know who is supposed to be
on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jayne O'Connor, a spokeswoman for Gov. Christie Whitman, said
state officials are looking into the possibility of allowing local
police to enforce the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ''The attorney general's office is researching the whole issue
right now,'' O'Connor said. ''The governor is aware that we need to
be mindful not to do anything that would prevent the delivery of
goods.''
</P>
<P>
   The watchdog group also requested that the state ban trucks
narrower than 102 inches. O'Connor said that, too, would be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   Hagerty, the State Police spokesman, said since May 20 troopers
have issued 175 summonses to trucks for violating the ban on local
roads.
</P>
<P>
   The American Trucking Associations, an industry trade group
based in Alexandria, Va., has filed a federal lawsuit challenging
the law.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unsafe, unfair and unconstitutional,'' said Mike Russell,
a spokesman for the group, which claims the ban violates the
Interstate Commerce clause of the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   That case is expected to be heard in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-16-00 1733 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000816.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pit Bull Owner Going to Jail  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUEN, France (AP) -- A French court on Wednesday convicted a man
of unleashing his pit bull on four people, including a police
officer, and sentenced him to spend six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The court in the northern city of Rouen found Jeremie Acquemin,
20, guilty of having his dog attack three people who refused to
give him change, which he was panhandling from passers-by. He also
was convicted of prodding the dog to attack a police officer who
tried to question him. The victims were hospitalized with dog
bites.
</P>
<P>
   The court gave Acquemin a two-year sentence with 18 months
suspended. It also ordered him to serve two years probation, seek
help for alcoholism and drug problems, pay $7,000 to the victims
and turn the dog over to authorities to be put to death.
</P>
<P>
   A series of brutal pit bull attacks has shocked France, and the
government has taken measures against the breed. France now
requires that pit bulls be castrated, registered and periodically
checked, and has outlawed their import and sale.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, Acquemin admitted that he removed the dog's
muzzle and ordered it to attack.
</P>
<P>
   He has been jailed since the attacks last month. The court
refused to release him after a prosecutor said that he was
''dangerous for having used his dog like a weapon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
