<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $Adv21  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Even Davy Crockett found New York City
frightening.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought I would rather risque myself in an Indian fight than
venture among these creatures after night,'' the legendary
frontiersman wrote after an 1835 visit.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers of the day agreed and clamored for safe streets. So
a night watch of moonlighting citizens began to patrol the city
and, in 1845, the first official police force was formed.
</P>
<P>
   The rich history of how the police grew from a ragtag bunch of
cigar-smoking men with no weapons to today's 40,000-strong force is
told in a book published this month, ''NYPD: A City And Its
Police.''
</P>
<P>
   Authors Thomas Reppetto and James Lardner have taken a broad
view they hope will give citizens - and officers - a true picture
of the nation's largest police force.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, too much attention has been paid to the repeated
charges of police corruption, said Lardner, a former Washington,
D.C., policeman and now a senior writer for U.S. News &AMP; World
Report.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you only see the corruption, you miss so much of the
history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 368-page book touches on the scandals but also offers little
known details - from the tidbit on Davy Crockett to the career of
William Bratton, the innovative police commissioner of the
mid-1990s known for his high-tech tactics against crime.
</P>
<P>
   Among the main characters are: the Presbyterian minister who
instigated the first efforts to reform the department; the first
black officer on the force; an Italian-American cop who made a
fatal, top-secret mission to Italy; two forgotten detectives with
an uncanny ability to catch crooks; and the commissioner deemed the
most effective by the authors.
</P>
<P>
   ''The book aimed to bring these characters to life,'' said
Reppetto, president of the city's Citizen Crime Commission and a
former Chicago police officer.
</P>
<P>
   The book, with its long view of history, does not concentrate on
the incidents that set off racial tension in recent years: the
police torture of Abner Louima, a Haitian immigrant, and the police
killings of West African immigrant Amadou Diallo and
Haitian-American Patrick Dorismond.
</P>
<P>
   ''We kind of let our history come to an end with Bratton,''
Lardner said. The Louima, Diallo and Dorismond cases happened under
Bratton's successor, Howard Safir, who is leaving the department
after four years.
</P>
<P>
   Readers learn how the Rev. Charles Parkhurst was ridiculed for
blaming the police for ''making New York a very hotbed of knavery,
debauchery, and bestiality.'' Determined to prove himself right,
Parkhurst went undercover in 1892 and exposed houses of ill-repute
rife with gambling and nude women.
</P>
<P>
   It was the NYPD's first - but certainly not last - big scandal.
Indeed, the book outlines a saga of scandal and reform that has
rocked the city at 20-year intervals since. It also covers a wide
range of tragedies and triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1909, one of the force's first Italian-American cops was sent
on a secret mission to Italy to investigate the Mafia. A
publicity-seeking police commissioner blabbed the details to the
press, blowing Lt. Joseph Petrosino's cover and leading to his
murder on the streets of Palermo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1911, Sam Battle became New York's first black policeman. He
was ignored by white colleagues but became a tourist attraction as
hansom cab drivers took fares past his beat near Central Park to
see him.
</P>
<P>
   A chapter called ''The Great Detective'' tells how Thomas Byrnes
organized the detective bureau into a real crimefighting squad in
the late 1800s, instituting the practice of photographing and
keeping files on criminals and allowing his men to branch off into
specialties, such as homicide.
</P>
<P>
   In a chapter on ''Celebrity Cops,'' Detective Johnny Cordes from
the 1920s is shown as a character Hollywood would love today. Since
he hated to carry a gun, he often had to disarm suspects before
arresting them. He once managed to disarm two burglars after being
shot - then was shot twice more by a drunken sergeant who stumbled
on the scene. He survived and returned to duty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cordes certainly seemed to have had a kind of cult of admirers
inside the force because people were just bowled over by his
doggedness,'' Lardner said.
</P>
<P>
   While Byrnes and Cordes were famous in their day, Lewis
Valentine toiled in anonymity as a ''shoofly,'' police slang in the
early 1900s for an internal affairs cop. Valentine was taunted for
years by fellow officers until Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia - admiring
his pursuit of bad cops - appointed him commissioner in 1934. He
went on to serve 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''He took over the force just as prohibition ended, when the
force was thoroughly corrupt,'' Reppetto said. ''He managed to end
a lot of the corruption so probably of all of them, he was the most
effective commissioner in the NYPD.''
</P>
<P>
   Among modern-day commissioners, Bratton is given an entire
chapter focusing on his introducing new concepts such as COMPSTAT,
a computerized tracking of crime statistics credited for helping
bring down crime rates to new lows.
</P>
<P>
   Reppetto said the little space given to Howard Safir's term was
not meant as a slight. Safir ''never quite got the credit for
keeping the crime reductions going,'' he said. ''He tried to move
toward the community with his CPR (courtesy, professionalism,
respect) program, but everytime something happened - Louima, then
Diallo, then Dorismond.''
</P>
<P>
   The book ends with an observation by Zachary Carter, a former
federal prosecutor who told a symposium on race relations: ''The
relationship between the police and inner-city residents is a love
affair waiting to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Reppetto and Lardner said Carter, a black man, is right.
Reppetto added that police in the past had difficulties with newly
arrived minorities - such as Irish and Italians - who eventually
became strong supporters of the police as their own members joined
the force.
</P>
<P>
   ''I suspect that will be the story in the early 21st century,
that the minority community will come to strongly support the
police,'' Reppetto said. ''The history of the NYPD suggests that
will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   ''NYPD: A City And Its Police,'' published by John Macrae
Book/Henry Holt &AMP; Co. $27.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
