<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artists step into the fray in effort to resolve MoMA strike  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE ROTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Strikers at the Museum of Modern Art this week
drew the support of the luminaries of the art world, including
artists Robert Rauschenberg and Art Spiegelman, filmmakers Steven
Spielberg and Martin Scorsese and performers Laurie Anderson and
David Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   The first strike in 27 years by museum employees - including
archivists, conservators, curators, librarians and other
professionals - has dragged on for more than three months. It's the
longest strike in the museum's history, yet neither side seems
willing to budge and each accuses the other of bargaining in bad
faith.
</P>
<P>
   Points of contention include salaries as well as union demands
for compulsory membership of professional staff.
</P>
<P>
   The artists' names were listed under a brief open letter
published in The Village Voice and Time Out New York this week
asking the public to respect the picket line in front of the museum
and expressing concern with what they called MoMA's refusal to
negotiate. A total of 131 names appear in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Union concerns ''deserve to be addressed in good-faith
bargaining sessions without further delay,'' said the letter in ad
space funded by the union.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by phone on Wednesday, Pulitzer Prize-winning New Yorker
illustrator Art Spiegelman said he had signed the letter partly
because a work of his would soon go on display at MoMA.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very upset. I'm going to feel very awkward if I have to
cross a picket line to see my work,'' he said. ''I did it for very
narcissistic reasons. I can't really in good conscience walk past
workers who are so cornered in a sense. ... I'd just like to see
this whole situation resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Other signers include filmmaker Pedro Almodovar, performing
artist Bill T. Jones, writers John Ashbery and Susan Sontag,
filmmakers Quentin Tarantino and Bertrand Tavernier and jazz
musician John Zorn.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the union did not immediately return calls
Wednesday seeking comment, but MoMA lawyer Robert Batterman said
the letter stems from a false assumption that the museum has
refused to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   ''What has happened is that the museum and the union have been
unable to reach an agreement. But there were nine months of
negotiations before the strike began and numerous conversations
through the mediators. I think signing such an open letter based on
the unilateral representation of the union is inappropriate and
will be recognized as such for people of good faith who read it
carefully,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Professional and Administrative Staff Association, Local
2110 of the United Auto Workers union, started the strike on April
28 after working for six months without a contract. There have been
no face-to-face negotiations since April 27 and none are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which represents 255 of the 650 museum employees,
says that museum salaries are too low, starting at $17,000, with a
median salary of $29,000. Another major complaint is job security:
The museum plans staff reductions during its expansion project, set
to begin in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Batterman has said the museum's latest contract offer amounts to
a 3 percent increase in wages and minimum salary each year for the
next three years, a better pension and dental plan, and a severance
package for any employees laid off during the expansion. MoMA's
wages are comparable to those at other museums across the country,
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
