<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aerial spraying in battle against West Nile  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Health officials, calling the next few weeks
critical in preventing human infection, are escalating the battle
against the West Nile virus with a one-two punch of ground spraying
and the season's first aerial spraying.
</P>
<P>
   ''It behooves us to really knock down the mosquito population,''
city Health Commissioner Neal Cohen said, noting that last year,
most of the seven victims who died were infected in August.
</P>
<P>
   ''The next two weeks up until Labor Day will certainly be very
critical for transmission,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   After another round of ground spraying on Wednesday evening, the
first aerial assault, with the pesticide Anvil, is scheduled for
Thursday night on Staten Island and in the Canarsie section of
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Three New Yorkers, all on Staten Island, have tested positive
for the virus and are undergoing treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight of the city's 36 virus-infected birds were found on
Staten Island. In Canarsie, a dead bird was confirmed to have West
Nile earlier this week. The neighborhood borders on tracts of empty
land and beaches where mosquitoes are likely to breed.
</P>
<P>
   At the Staten Island Zoo, a snowy-white owl died July 31 after
contracting the virus. His female cagemate died two weeks later,
but zoo officials have not yet received results of the lab tests on
the second bird.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ground-based spraying was planned for Brooklyn's
Prospect Park and Greenwood Cemetery on Friday and Saturday nights.
Five live birds collected at the cemetery have tested positive.
</P>
<P>
   The virus apparently survived the winter in hibernating insects.
But many of the mosquitoes and their larvae were destroyed in an
early campaign to eliminate breeding sites.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, hundreds of birds and tens of thousands of
mosquitoes were tested, while insect repellant was sprayed last
month from trucks around the city, the northern suburbs and Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the mosquito population rises tenfold every two
weeks and was expected to peak this week.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in addition to the seven New Yorkers who died, 62
were treated for West Nile. The most severe infections may result
in encephalitis, an inflammation of the brain, or meningitis, an
inflammation of the brain's lining and the spinal cord.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
