<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FTC charges company over attention disorder supplement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - The Federal Trade Commission charged a New
York company Wednesday with making unsubstantiated claims that its
dietary supplement can treat children with attention disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Natural Organics Inc., of Melville, N.Y., claims in advertising
that its Pedi-Active A.D.D. supplement can alleviate symptoms of
attention deficit hyperactivity disorder and improve the attention
span of children who have difficulty focusing on schoolwork, the
FTC said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''ADHD is a serious condition, and parents who are concerned
about it should talk to their children's doctors about appropriate
treatment,'' said Jodie Bernstein, director of the FTC's Bureau of
Consumer Protection. She asserted that the company's ads prey on
parents seeking alternative treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Physician-prescribed stimulants and behavior therapy are the
most common treatment for ADHD, which affects up to 2.5 million
school-age children in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Natural Organics did not immediately return calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which does business as ''Nature's Plus,'' markets
and sells a variety of dietary supplements through independent
retail stores. Sixty tablets of Pedi-Active A.D.D. sell for $12.56.
</P>
<P>
   This is the FTC's fifth action involving products marketed to
treat ADHD. While the commission's complaint begins a legal process
seeking to stop future unsupported claims, it doesn't mean any laws
have been broken.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Trade Commission: http://www.ftc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-16-00 1803 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000816.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> After detailing allegations of abuse, judge waits for decision  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The one-time Family Court judge was herself
a witness Wednesday, spilling out allegations of infidelities and
abuse in an attempt to keep her job.
</P>
<P>
   Now state Superior Court Judge Rosemarie Williams must wait for
word from a disciplinary committee on the penalty for her public
dispute with a former boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 48, admitted it was a mistake to confront Alfred
''Wes'' Bridges, 27, and his female companion at a restaurant on
April 14. The judge said she erred again by following the couple to
a Trenton bar.
</P>
<P>
   Her hindsight comes from counseling she sought after the final
confrontation of their two-year relationship, Williams testified.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's first public hearing for a Superior Court judge
ended Wednesday with testimony from Williams, who offered sometimes
graphic details about alleged abuse. The state says her conduct
April 14 was a violation of judicial ethics and it could mean
removal from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier domestic dispute with Bridges cost Williams a chance
at tenure, the judge revealed Wednesday. She was also chastised by
her superiors and reassigned to Somerset County to keep her away
from Bridges, who worked as a sheriff's officer in the Mercer
County courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Williams claimed she helped Bridges get into law school. She
paid for entrance exams, prep classes and later wrote letters of
recommendation, Williams said. Once enrolled, Williams said she
aided with his homework.
</P>
<P>
   Williams repeatedly denied that she shouted profanities the
night of April 14. The accusation that she posed as a police
officer in a later telephone call was a misunderstanding, Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said something to the effect of I'm calling from the
Hopewell police,'' Williams said, telling the panel she was using
her cell phone while in the police station's parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said she did call Bridges' answering machine that night
and made several negative comments about companion Tami DeVitas'
appearance. Saying she was a ''skinny, scrawny little girlfriend''
was her attempt to attack Bridge's vanity, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge claimed her former paramour would only date
''brilliant, gorgeous'' women.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also admitted saying something to DeVitas at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ''To be a wise guy,'' Williams said. ''I said she was ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   But the judge steadfastly denied using a vulgar term to describe
the woman.
</P>
<P>
   ''I basically had a moment of clarity, bit the side of my cheek
and said something to myself,'' Williams said. ''At that moment, I
looked around and said 'What am I doing here?'''
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, the lawyer for the Advisory Committee on
Judicial Conduct asked Williams why she just didn't get up and
leave when she spotted Bridges come into the restaurant
</P>
<P>
   ''Basic human decency was I was here first,'' she said. ''I just
thought the decent thing for him to do was to leave. He didn't have
reservations.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee, headed by retired Supreme Court Associate Justice
Alan Handler, peppered Williams with questions. Many wanted to know
if Williams found any potential conflict in her romantic
relationship with a law enforcement officer while she handled
criminal or juvenile cases.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said she saw no problem and said she thought her
judicial superiors were of the same mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sheriff's officers, in my mind, are not the same as Trenton
police,'' Williams said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
