<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> An analysis of Lazio ad stressing his legislative work  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   An analysis of the new Lazio campaign ad regarding
Republican
Senate candidate Rick Lazio's Congressional record:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TITLE: ''Effective.''
</P>
<P>
   LENGTH: 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Murphy Pintak Gautier Hudome Agency.
</P>
<P>
   AIRING: Upstate New York markets Wednesday, statewide on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPT: (Read by a male announcer) ''The Quality Housing Act to
dramatically improve public housing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Empowering Our Educators Act to get better trained
teachers into the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Breast and Cervical Cancer Treatment Act to help
low-income women get treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are all signed pieces of legislation that have passed
the U.S. Congress. Who is the Congressman behind all this
legislation? Rick Lazio - 8 very effective years in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rick Lazio - from New York, for New York.''
</P>
<P>
   IMAGES: Black background, white letters with the title of each
act appearing as it's read. The titles of several other acts
sponsored or supported by Lazio also appear on the screen. As the
announcer poses his final question, video of Lazio marching in an
upstate New York Fourth of July parade appears.
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: Patrick McCarthy, a campaign spokesman, says the ad is
intended to contrast Lazio's voting record with his opponent,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, who has never held elective office.
</P>
<P>
   The ad is a stark, serious, issue-oriented piece intended to set
the record straight on some of the Clinton campaign's allegations
about Lazio's record. It also strikes Lazio's continuing theme of a
homegrown New York candidate versus an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokeswoman Karen Dunn responded by saying the
spot attempts to obscure Lazio's record.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rick Lazio is taking credit for one bill that hasn't passed,
one bill he stole, and one bill he delayed for three years,'' she
said, referring respectively to the education bill, the Breast and
Cervical Cancer Treatment Act, and the housing legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Analysis by Frank Eltman, Associated Press Writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
