<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bird-biting mosquitoes found in Norwalk, but health officials have no plans to spray </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Bird-biting mosquitoes infected with the
West Nile virus have been found in Norwalk, but state officials
said Wednesday they do not plan any new pesticide spraying as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   The mosquitoes, of the culex restuans variety, were collected
Aug. 7 at Cranbury Park, in the northern section of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The finding ''does not represent a direct threat to people,''
said state epidemiologist Dr. James Hadler. There have been no
human cases reported in Connecticut this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But, ''we might be closer to the day when the human-biting
mosquitoes become infected,'' Hadler said.
</P>
<P>
   The state will not spray pesticide in Norwalk because the virus
is now too widespread, and the spraying would be inaffective, said
Joxel Garcia, commissioner of the Department of Public Health. Last
month, the DEP sprayed a two-mile radius of Stamford, Darien and
New Canaan with insecticide when the virus was found in the same
type of mosquito in a Stamford park.
</P>
<P>
   Officials on Wednesday also announced the discovery of three
additional crows infected with the virus - two in Norwalk and one
in Milford. To date, a total of 39 crows with the virus have been
found in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The virus first surfaced in the region last year, killing seven
people - all of whom were over 75 - and sickening 62 others in New
York. It also killed hundreds of birds in Connecticut, New York and
New Jersey. There have been three human cases reported in New York
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who contract the disease experience flu-like
symptoms and never realize they have been exposed to the virus. The
virus can lead to a potentially fatal form of encephalitis, an
inflammation of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Officials continued to encourage state residents to protect
themselves against mosquito bites by using repellant, covering up
with long shirts and pants and avoiding outdoor activities during
peak mosquito hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to avoid being bitten by mosquitoes,'' Garcia said.
''We have to do the prevention part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
