<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 59; Nasdaq Is Up 10  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices closed mixed Wednesday, as
investors digested the dual effects of modest inflation brought
about by a cooling economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 58.61 at 11,008.39.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 4.58 at 1,479.85, and the Nasdaq composite index
finished up 9.54 at 3,861.20.
</P>
<P>
   A selloff in retail stocks helped drag down the Dow index. Home
Depot fell $2.375 to $51.375, and Wal-Mart Stores was down $1.875
to $49.875.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sold retail stocks in the fear that second-half
profits could fall short of expectations if consumer spending eases
in step with the Federal Reserve Board's policy of cooling the
economy to fight inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Economic data released Wednesday provided further evidence that
the Fed's strategy to slow the economy may be working.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you have slowing economic growth, there are two effects.
First, there is reduced pressure for the Federal Reserve Board to
increase interest rates,'' said Richard Hoey, chief economist and
chief investment strategist at Dreyfus Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, a slower economy also creates less robust
expectations for corporate profits, especially in the retail
sector,'' Hoey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department's Consumer Price Index, a widely watched
barometer for inflation, showed that consumer prices rose a mild
0.2 percent last month, as the cost of gasoline eased after soaring
in June.
</P>
<P>
   The CPI's core rate, which excludes the volatile food and energy
sectors, also rose just 0.2 percent, for a fourth consecutive
month, suggesting that most other prices remain under control.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that the economy is cooling, the Commerce
Department reported Wednesday that housing construction fell 3.3
percent in July to the lowest level in at least two years. It was
the third straight monthly decline.
</P>
<P>
   If the Fed, which has raised interest rates six times in the
past 14 months, feels their economic tightening plan is working,
interest rates will likely be left unchanged at the Fed's next
meeting Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The markets have lacked a clear direction for weeks ahead of the
Fed meeting, fluctuating from day to day based on earnings reports
or economic data.
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors are pretty complacent right now. There's no reason
for them to make a decision one way or the other. Why ruffle any
feathers?'' said Sal Calabrese, managing director of U.S. listed
equities at Dresdner Bank in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Profit taking in the financial services sector left those stocks
down across the board.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of technology stocks helped keep the Nasdaq in
positive territory. Online auctioneer eBay led Nasdaq gainers,
jumping $5.625 to $57.50. Internet portal companies Yahoo!, up
$1.687 to $134, and Lycos, up $3.125 to $61.063, also provided a
lift.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume came to 1.13
billion shares, up from Tuesday's pace of 1.09 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 2.81 at 512.74.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.35 percent.
Germany's DAX index was up 0.11 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up
0.87 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.72 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
