<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York delegates are wined and dined at Democratic Convention  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) - It was hard to miss the lobster tails at the
New York convention party at Spago. The blonde woman in full
mermaid dress hired to lounge on a nearby fountain was a dead
giveaway that the lavish buffet of lobster, mussels, shrimp and
sushi was nearby.
</P>
<P>
   At the bar, New York's real-life politicos mingled with the
actors who play politicos on the television drama ''The West
Wing.'' Champagne glasses were kept full by an attentive fleet of
servers.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the scene at the bash thrown by financial news mogul
Michael Bloomberg, who flew several burly New York City cops to Los
Angeles to keep all but the invited guests out on the curb.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg, who has been mentioned as a possible candidate for
New York City mayor next year, reportedly spent over $100,000 on
the soiree.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it, New York delegates are being wined and dined
in style at the Democratic National Convention, where a host of
corporations and interest groups seem to be gambling that the best
way to delegates hearts is through their stomachs. Companies such
as Kodak, Pfizer and Global Crossing are among those picking up the
tab.
</P>
<P>
   Some have strong New York ties.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone giant Worldcom, which co-sponsored a buffet breakfast
for the delegation, has concerns about Bell Atlantic's plan to
begin offering long-distance service in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak is New York's largest employer. It is also under close
scrutiny from the state as one of its largest corporate polluters.
Still, the film giant footed the bill for New York's opening night
reception where guests could get their picture taken against a
backdrop that simulated the Oval Office or with a real White House
resident - U.S. Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   New York's events are not illegal. Nor are they unique.
Corporate sponsors are pouring money into large numbers of events
for delegates from across the nation. But as a large state that is
the hub of the financial services industry, New York is being
treated particularly well.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is entirely unseemly,'' said Rachel Leon, of the New York
chapter of Common Cause. ''It appears that both these conventions
are being bought and run by corporations and what happened to the
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   State Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver brushed aside the
criticism and said the sponsors were just being ''good corporate
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It gives these corporations the opportunity to put their name
forward so people can see it at a relatively small price,'' said
Silver, who is leading the New York delegation.
</P>
<P>
   For the price of omelets, danishes, coffee and juice for several
hundred, Global Crossing Chief Executive Gary Winneck was given
time to address the New York delegation just before former Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin and the Rev. Jesse Jackson on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Winneck spoke for so long about his New York roots and the
success of his telecommunications upstart company, that Jackson -
waiting in the audience as the featured speaker - gathered his
aides to leave. Sen. Charles Schumer hustled to the back of the
room and persuaded Jackson to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Individual politicians have also benefited from corporate
largesse at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller H. Carl McCall, who is looking to run for
governor in 2002, was supposed to have his reception sponsored by
Verizon. The strike scuttled those plans for the union-friendly
Democrat. Instead another utility, Keyspan stepped in and paid the
tab. Keyspan was created by the merger of Long Island Lighting
Company and Brooklyn Union Gas.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita Lowey's women and government event was paid for by
Chase Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, who won his seat by
attacking the ethics of his GOP opponent Dennis Vacco, paused
thoughtfully on Wednesday before volunteering his thoughts on the
heavy corporate imprint on the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything that is being done is meticulously in compliance
not only with the rules that are there but with the spirit so I
have no problem with it on that level,'' Spitzer said. But Spitzer,
a millionaire who bankrolled much of his own campaign, said as the
state's top lawyer he had chosen to forego corporate sponsorship
for any of his own events.
</P>
<P>
   'In my case particularly I would feel some sense of
discomfort,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
