<HEADLINE> Sky diver on first solo jump blows off course into trees  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MONROE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - A sky diver making his first solo
jump got blown two miles off course Wednesday and had to be rescued
from treetops, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Pavic, 27, of Roslyn, Pa., was one of two student
parachutists making their first solo jump. They left Free Fall
Adventures in Williamstown at about 8 a.m., police said.
</P>
<P>
   Winds carried both divers about two miles east of their intended
landing zone. One student landed safely in a field, but Pavic
descended in a heavily wooded area near the border of Winslow
Township.
</P>
<P>
   His parachute got stuck in the top of two 75-foot-tall oak
trees, and Pavic was dangling and stuck on branches, said Sgt. Tony
Pace.
</P>
<P>
   Two volunteer firefighters climbed to near the tops of the trees
to rescue him.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only difficult moments took place when a news helicopter
flew so near as to drown out the rescuers' shouted instructions to
the dangling parachutist,'' Pace said.
</P>
<P>
   Pavic was lowered to the ground about two hours after landing in
the tree tops.
</P>
</TEXT>
