<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man accused of stealing 120 weapons from Va. gunmaker he worked for </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A Newark native who had managed a Virginia
warehouse for a firearms maker was in federal court Wednesday,
accused of stealing 120 handguns from his former employer.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Guzman Jr. apparently mailed two packages containing some
of the high-powered weapons from the Heckler &AMP; Koch warehouse in
Sterling, Va., to Newark in late March, one to a friend and one to
his mother's home, according to charges filed by the U.S. Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco &AMP; Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman ''unexpectedly'' resigned from H&AMP;K in April, days after
ATF advised the company that two weapons the company believed were
in the warehouse had been found in Newark, the ATF charges said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight more of the guns have been recovered in connection with
crimes this spring in northern New Jersey, including two attempted
murders, ATF Special Agent Joseph G. Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Agents searching the Belleville home where Guzman had been
staying with an aunt did not uncover the missing weapons, but did
find two empty H&AMP;K magazines and two bulletproof vests, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's one of our top priorities, to recover those 110
handguns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman was arrested Tuesday afternoon at the home without
incident, ATF said.
</P>
<P>
   The .40-caliber and 9mm semiautomatic weapons are
''high-quality, well-made firearms'' that sell for at least $700
and have fetched $1,000 in undercover street sales, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman, 27, was ordered held on $100,000 bail by U.S. Magistrate
Susan D. Davis. If he makes bail, Guzman must stay with his mother
under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Louis Valentin said Guzman has six
lawfully obtained weapons, which Davis ordered Guzman to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman faces a single charge of trafficking in stolen firearms,
which carries up to 10 years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman's aunt, Vivian Sosa, is a Newark police officer, Valentin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Newark police said Sosa, 32, has cooperated with the
investigation and has not been implicated at this time. Sosa will
remain on full duty while the department's internal affairs office
investigates, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Green said, ''At this point, we don't think she had anything to
do with this operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Guzman did not speak during the 10-minute bail hearing, aside to
acknowledge he had a lawyer, John D. Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   Caruso said Guzman has no prior arrests and intends to plead
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman's mother declined to speak with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A request for comment from H&AMP;K was not immediately returned
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After H&AMP;K told ATF that weapons found in Newark appeared to be
in its warehouse, ATF asked the company to conduct an inventory,
which revealed three missing boxes, each containing 40 weapons,
Green said.
</P>
<P>
   The packages Guzman sent weighed 19.6 pounds and 34.2 pounds,
ATF court papers said. Since each handgun weighs about 5 pounds,
''Those two packages sent didn't represent all of the missing
firearms,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman began working for H&AMP;K in January 1996 and was promoted to
warehouse manager in November 1999, according to the ATF charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
