<HEADLINE> Government To Pay Down Debt  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government plans to pay down $17.7 billion
on the federal debt next week by selling two-year notes, the
Treasury Department announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The notes, to be sold next Wednesday, will be available in
minimum denominations of $1,000 and will mature on Aug. 31, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced early this month that the government
will pay down $221 billion of publicly-held debt this year,
bringing to $360 billion the amount of public debt reduced over the
past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department is reducing the debt in two ways. In one
of them, it is for the first time in decades actually buying back
debt held by the public. Officials hope to trim the debt by $30
billion this year through buybacks.
</P>
<P>
   The other method is through Treasury's more conventional
refinancing operations, in which it sells new debt at auctions such
as next week's to redeem securities coming due on a regular basis.
The amount of new securities sold is smaller than the amount of
securities coming due, thereby reducing the total debt held by the
public.
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of the government's reduced borrowing needs at a
time of big government surpluses, Treasury officials have said they
are continuing to study the possibility of eliminating sales of the
one-year T-bill.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury has already cut back sales of the one-year bill from
once a month to once every three months, and before that it
eliminated sales of three-year notes completely.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, while good for taxpayers because they mean lower
interest payments on the national debt, pose challenges for
investors because they shrink the supply of Treasury securities,
considered the world's safest investment.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said Tuesday that even with
a huge budget surplus, tax-cutting restraint still is needed and
the government should continue whittling the debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a different economy ... and that's why it's so important
that we keep paying down our debt. ... It has never been more
important to maintain our fiscal discipline,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's budget calls for eliminating the $3.6
trillion of debt held by the public by 2012. The total national
debt is $5.6 trillion, which includes not only the publicly-held
debt but also debt held by government trust funds, including Social
Security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-16-00 1900 </TRAILER>
