<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Detail Submarine Conditions  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH B. VERRENGIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's as dark as the inside of a blindfold. Your breathing slips
into shallow panting as precious oxygen ebbs. It's so cold that the
sweat and tears of your terrified shipmates turns to slick frost on
bare metal.
</P>
<P>
   After five days sitting 354 feet below the churning Barents Sea,
the crippled Russian submarine Kursk rapidly is becoming a steel
coffin for its crew of 116, if they haven't already perished,
veteran submariners say.
</P>
<P>
   The deep is unforgiving. That's what submariners -- some of whom
have survived accidents dating back to World War II -- know as they
await the fate of the Russians sailors who until recently were
their foes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It must be terrifically damp, dark and cold,'' said Steve
Collier of Bath, Ohio, a retired U.S. Navy master chief petty
officer who served on three submarines from 1973-93.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk is lying awkwardly on its side in strong currents and
swirling muck, frustrating repeated rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say the bow probably was damaged by an
explosion, perhaps in a torpedo bay. Several compartments flooded
with sea water, sending the sub to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans submariners say the sailors in the Kursk's bow almost
certainly are dead. Survivors are more likely to have been
stationed in the rear of the vessel. Watertight bulkheads probably
have split the crew into small groups, adding to their sense of
vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every submariner knows that tomorrow it could happen to him,''
said retired Russian Capt. Valerei Zelichonok, who commanded
submarines before moving to Israel in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   For Dan Persico of Amsterdam, N.Y., the Russian ordeal recalls
the 48 harrowing hours he spent trapped aboard the USS Squalus,
which sunk in 240 feet of water off New Hampshire in 1939.
Twenty-six men died. Persico was among 33 survivors who rode to the
surface in a nine-ton diving bell lowered by a rescue ship.
</P>
<P>
   The Squalus disaster began when a mechanical failure during a
training exercise flooded the submarine's engine rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Persico, now 80, was a 20-year-old sailor in the forward torpedo
room. He and the other sailors laid on the floor of the tilted sub
in silence for nearly 24 hours. The rescue took another day to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   But even then, the Squalus crew had advantages the Russians in
this case don't have, Persico said. ''We were in radio contact,''
he said. ''We knew the rescue ship was on its way.''
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for help, the Kursk's sailors might be lying still
in the pitch-black of their bunks or hunkered at their
workstations.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't count on anyone from the outside, but you hope
somebody will get lucky,'' Collier said. ''You've known in the back
of your mind that this was possible. But the more you do, the more
oxygen you use. So you sit tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Failed rescue attempts by a mini-sub that cannot latch onto the
Kursk's hatches probably are draining the crew's hope.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've heard the submersibles. They probably don't have much
heart,'' said retired U.S. Navy Capt. Don Walsh, who shares the
record for the deepest dive -- 32,748 feet into the Marianas Trench
in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Modern subs are high-tech marvels that can circumnavigate the
globe without surfacing, from the polar ice caps to trenches deeper
than the Grand Canyon. At 14,000 tons, the nuclear-powered Kursk is
one of 11 Oscar II-class submarines and one of the more capable in
the Russian fleet.
</P>
<P>
   But when disaster strikes, modern subs are not much better than
their cramped predecessors during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, veterans say: drill, drill, drill. But few American
submariners have faced circumstances as grim as those aboard the
Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   Collier, now an environmental engineer at a former nuclear
weapons plant, supervised emergency training on the USS Baton
Rouge. He operated nuclear propulsion systems on two others. He
served several tours in the Barents Sea playing cat-and-mouse games
against the Russians, isolated for six months at a stretch ''with
no sunlight, no women, no fresh milk after the third day.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier devised disaster simulations during underwater missions.
For smoke, he would make the crew operate the sub blindfolded or
wearing hoods. For explosions, he pulsed water through the torpedo
tubes to rock the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Zelichonok, the former Russian sub commander, said Russian crews
practice in the dark, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''You switch off the lights and you do it again,'' he said.
''Submariners are like iron. I'm sure every man knew what he had to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is no drill.
</P>
<P>
   It's sea-floor dark. Russian officials say the sub's nuclear
reactors were turned off or failed after the accident. The sub's
large batteries would be drained within two or three days. Electric
lanterns and flashlights probably have dimmed, too.
</P>
<P>
   It's cold. The surrounding water temperature is well below
freezing. Residual heat in the sub's pipes has long since
dissipated, making it little more than a metal can in an icy bath.
</P>
<P>
   Sailors might be wrapped in blankets. But in the mechanical
areas to the rear of the sub, they probably have no extra clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Humidity, even from the men's breathing, turns to ice on exposed
metal.
</P>
<P>
   And it's suffocating. The Russian sub may have an oxygen-making
system, but it would rely on electricity, too. Oxygen tanks may
have been damaged in the wreck and they're probably depleting now.
</P>
<P>
   Such claustrophobia haunts every submariner -- or ''bubblehead''
in their jargon. Even under normal conditions, the slightest change
in air quality sends a ripple of quiet panic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would get upset when the fire in my cigarette would go
out,'' Collier recalled. ''Some crewman had allowed the oxygen
concentration to drop a bit low. But the Kursk crew would be happy
with that oxygen level compared to what they have now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
