<HEADLINE> Germany Vows To Fight Neo-Nazis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Faced with a wave of neo-Nazi violence, the German
Cabinet on Wednesday approved $35 million in spending over three
years to support youth programs fighting racism, anti-Semitism and
hatred of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The government also will establish a nationwide hotline people
can use to alert police to ''drunken skinheads'' on the streets,
and has set up a $4.7 million fund to help victims of neo-Nazi
violence, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Family Ministry said the money would support projects that
try to integrate young people into careers and society and combat
right-wing extremism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Short-term, one-time actions aren't enough,'' said Edith
Niehuis, a top ministry official. ''We have to help build up
structures and networks to have a long-term bulwark against
right-wing radicalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Although alienated young men often are the ones involved in
attacks on foreigner and Jews, Niehuis said it was wrong to lay all
the blame for neo-Nazi violence on youth.
</P>
<P>
   ''They can act that way only because they meet with agreement or
approval or people look away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, an administrative court in Berlin upheld the
city's decision to deny a parade permit to a neo-Nazi who wanted to
mark this week's anniversary of the death of Adolf Hitler's deputy,
Rudolf Hess.
</P>
<P>
   The court said such a march would be ''unbearable'' for the
general public, especially considering recent violence against
foreigners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
