<HEADLINE> State creates harness racing monitoring panel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Two weeks after a harness driver was
sentenced to probation for his part in a conspiracy to fix races,
the New Jersey Racing Commission created a task force to review
racing practices.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a regulatory body, we have an obligation to enhance racing
integrity. We equally have an obligation to maintain and foster
public confidence in the sport of harness racing,'' commission
Chairman Noel Love Gross said in a statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the state's racing commissioners will be joined by staff
members and others with racing experience.
</P>
<P>
   The panel will evaluate racing trends ''to determine if they
fall within the appropriate parameters,'' Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   Task force members will also evaluate industry concerns on drug
testing, licensing and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Meadowlands Race Track, Garden State Park and
Freehold Raceway support the initiative, Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 5, a Superior Court judge sentenced driver Richard
Wojcio to five years probation and fined him $7,500. Wojcio also
was ordered to perform 500 hours of community service, which he has
already completed.
</P>
<P>
   Wojcio won 405 races and more than $2.4 million in purse money
in 1995, the year before his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators accused him of conspiring with drivers before
three races in which he had bet. They claimed he helped other
drivers place second or third in two of those races.
</P>
<P>
   A jury convicted Wojcio in 1998 of conspiring to fix races at
Freehold Raceway. He was cleared of charges of fixing races.
</P>
</TEXT>
