<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State says it doesn't closely monitor dam repairs  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPARTA, N.J. (AP) - As owners of burst dams that drained lakes
and washed out roads in torrential flooding struggle to repair
them, a state official acknowledged that New Jersey has not
aggressively regulated most of its dams over the years to make sure
they get fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't keep such a close eye on them,'' State Department of
Environmental Protection spokesman Peter Page said Wednesday of the
more than 1,400 dams in the state considered to not pose a
life-threatening danger if they break.
</P>
<P>
   The dams are inspected every two to four years, he said, but
when it comes to making sure the dams get repaired, ''it's much
more of an honor system.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials, dam owners and residents near the destructive
floods in northwestern New Jersey all believe that vigilant repairs
couldn't have prevented four Sussex County dams from breaking last
Saturday, when more than a foot of rain fell on some areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just an act of God,'' said Katherine Bakka, whose home
sits across from a muddy, 25-acre hole in the ground that was once
Seneca Lake. ''That water is powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Water pushed through Seneca Lake's earthen dam Saturday night,
draining it in about an hour. The water rushed downstream to
Tomahawk Lake and broke through its dam, emptying the lake that was
part of a private water park.
</P>
<P>
   Also destroyed were the Edison Pond dam in Sparta and the
Furnace Pond dam in Stanhope. Five other earthen dams in Sparta
remained under heavy scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Pietranowicz, treasurer of the 150-member Seneca Lake
Association, said the association was hoping for government aid to
spend about $200,000 to repair the dam. Residents who jointly own
the 50-year-old lake pay $180 annual dues to maintain it.
</P>
<P>
   Pietranowicz said the association had repaired the dam over the
years, removing brush, restoring erosion and inspecting a spillway
for cracks. But in the five years he has been treasurer, he says
the state has not notified him of any problems with the dam.
</P>
<P>
   John H. Moyle, chief of the DEP's dam safety section, told The
New York Times and The Record of Hackensack that the dam had
problems in 1991 that were never repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Pietranowicz said he has since found a 1981 state inspection
report noting problems with the dam's spillway, and a 1994 letter
from Moyle asking for a required permit to complete dam repairs
that are not specified. Pietranowicz was unaware of the letters
before the dam broke on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm still going through boxes trying to find out the history
of all this,'' Pietranowicz said.
</P>
<P>
   Page said only 187 of the 1,600 dams in the state are classified
as ''high hazard,'' meaning they would pose a life-threatening
danger if they burst. Those dams are inspected every two years and
when owners don't complete repairs on time, they are mailed letters
and orders and, as a last resort, sued by the state Attorney
General's Office, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state is less vigilant about the dams classified as low or
significant hazard, Page said.
</P>
<P>
   Seneca Lake dam was considered a significant hazard because it
threatened property damage if it burst, and gets inspected every
two years, Page said. The other three dams that burst were
considered low hazards, and are inspected every four years, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The responsibility for repairs lies with private owners, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For residents of Seneca Lake, who lost an ecosystem where
osprey, beavers and otters fed on other wildlife, it doesn't matter
whose fault it is that the dam broke.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issue is the lake is emptied out. There's an ecosystem
here that's going to be destroyed,'' said Gordon Bonker, a resident
for 37 years. ''I want to see water back in here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
