<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Visit Tanzania  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will visit Tanzania this
month to show U.S. support for the Burundi peace process being
mediated by former South African President Nelson Mandela, the
White House announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela invited Clinton to join him Aug. 28 in Arusha, where
they will meet with Benjamin Mkapa, president of the southeastern
African nation situated on the Indian Ocean. The White House did
not disclose any other details about Clinton's trip, but Aug. 28 is
the deadline Mandela set for the signing of a peace agreement to
end an ethnic war in neighboring Burundi between the Tutsis, who
control the government, and Hutu rebels.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1999, Mandela began to broker negotiations between
Burundi officials and opposition leaders to end the seven-year
conflict that has claimed the lives of at least 200,000 people,
most of them civilians, and displaced 1.2 million others.
</P>
<P>
   Before going to Tanzania, Clinton is scheduled to be on the
west-central coast of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   From Aug. 25 to 27, he is to meet with Nigerian President
Olusegun Obasanjo. The two, who met at the White House last
October, plan to discuss U.S. support for democratic transformation
in Nigeria under Obasanjo, who pledged to curb corruption and
stabilize democratic rule when he took office last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
