<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood evacuees returning to their homes  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKETTSTOWN, N.J. (AP) - Some 200 Byram residents returned home
Wednesday morning after the rising Musconetcong River forced their
evacuations two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Downpours on Monday and Saturday damaged thousands of homes,
wiped out dozens of bridges, roads and dams, and forced hundreds of
people to flee the rising waters.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency officials said the river is receding.
</P>
<P>
   Byram Township Patrolman John D'Onofrio said the river has
receded 2 feet within the last two days. ''We're in pretty good
shape,'' D'Onofrio said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, emergency officials resumed the search for a
kayaker who went out on the swollen Musconetcong River. Crews were
searching the river between Holland Township in Hunterdon County
and Pohatcong in Warren County, according to the Hunterdon County
dispatch center.
</P>
<P>
   Holland Township police said the search ended Wednesday night
and was scheduled to resume Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   An official said the area being searched is near where the
Musconetcong goes into the Delaware River.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities identified the missing man as Charles Weaver, 58, of
Riegelsville.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state is awaiting word from the Clinton
administration on Gov. Christie Whitman's request to declare Morris
and Sussex counties federal disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman put both counties under a state of emergency, allowing
the state to order evacuations and activate New Jersey National
Guard units to help residents.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Warren County also were inundated.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Senator Robert Torricelli on Tuesday asked President
Clinton to support the governor's request.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she spoke with Federal Emergency Management Agency
Director James Lee Witt Wednesday morning. Damage in the two
counties is significant, and the federal agency has all necessary
paperwork from New Jersey, Witt told Whitman, according to a
statement from the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Witt is aware of the situation confronting residents of the
areas affected by the flooding, and he assured me that FEMA would
act on our request for a federal disaster declaration as soon as
possible,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor expects ''a decision from Washington in the next
several days,'' said Laura Otterbourg, a spokeswoman from Whitman's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Otterbourg said if Sussex and Morris counties are declared
federal disaster areas, a Federal Emergency Management Agency
office would be set up in the area to assist residents.
</P>
<P>
   The damage cost will surpass $100 million, Whitman spokesman
Peter McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   An early estimate of flood-related damage in Morris County was
about $12 million, said Rick Loock, county deputy emergency
management coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Eskil ''Skip'' Danielson, Sussex County emergency management
coordinator, said $166 million is an accurate damage estimate. That
figure includes property that would be covered by insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Warren County officials said there was no structural damage
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Floodwaters in Jefferson Township have receded, authorities
there said. Police Chief John Palko put flood damages at $7 million
to $10 million, with $380,000 in damage to bridges and roads.
</P>
<P>
   Two roads, including the busy Dover-Milton Road, in Jefferson
remain closed Wednesday afternoon. In addition, 20 homes have been
left uninhabitable.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross spokeswoman Cathy Derechailo said at least 400 homes
in Jefferson Township had some flood-related damage.
</P>
<P>
   State police spokesman John Hagerty said 2,700 residences and
businesses in Sussex and Morris counties reported flood-related
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said about 1,000 homes in Sussex County were
evacuated since Saturday and 500 residents were evacuated at some
point.
</P>
<P>
   About 51 homes in Sparta had some flood damage, township manager
Henry Underhill said Tuesday. At least three of the homes are
probably total losses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   State emergency workers said 11 bridges in Sussex County
remained closed Tuesday due to water damage, flooding and erosion.
</P>
<P>
   Sussex County officials said Wednesday they plan to erect four
temporary bridges - three in Sparta and one in Ogdensburg - in
several days.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross officials said they are distributing cleanup kits that
include mops and cleansers to kill mold, which one official called
''a huge problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It evolves into black mold which is very serious and can be
harmful to your health,'' Derechailo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
