<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentines Exhort Albright on Files  </HEADLINE>
By BILL CORMIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright promised Wednesday to do what she can to push for
declassification of U.S. files about past South American
dictatorships accused of cracking down on dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States wants to be as cooperative and helpful as
possible in trying to understand better what happened in a series
of tragic situations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's comments came after a morning meeting with relatives
of people who disappeared during Argentina's 1976-83 ''Dirty War.''
During the meeting, the leaders of two Argentine human rights
groups asked Albright to declassify the files.
</P>
<P>
   Estela Carlotto -- a leader of Grandmothers of the Plaza de Mayo,
a human rights group that has pressed for information about
relatives who disappeared under Argentina's former military rulers
-- told reporters that Washington must open up more classified files
from the era.
</P>
<P>
   She said human rights groups especially want information about
the so-called Operation Condor in which past military governments --
Argentina, Chile, Brazil and Paraguay among them -- are accused of
cooperating in a cross-border hunt for leftist foes in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference alongside Argentine Foreign
Minister Rodriguez Giavarini, Albright said the United States had
already begun opening its files on Chile. She said more documents
were expected to released in September at the request of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president has asked all the agencies to be as forthcoming
as possible ... in releasing documents, and I believe we are living
up to that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina has acknowledged that some 9,000 people disappeared
under the former dictatorship, but human rights groups claim as
many as 30,000 died or disappeared during the ''dirty war''
crackdown on leftist opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina is one of Washington's strongest allies in the
hemisphere. With only a few months remaining in the Clinton
administration, Albright's visit was rich with symbolism, including
a wreath-laying Wednesday before the statue of an Argentine
independence hero.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Albright was to visit a new Jewish community center
built on the site of a 1994 terrorist bombing that killed 86
people. The United States has thrown its support behind renewed
Argentine efforts to prosecute the masterminds of that bombing and
of the 1992 bombing of the Israeli embassy here.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's five-day, five-nation South American tour began
Tuesday in Brazil, where she underscored commitments to strengthen
democracy and free trade across the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke of a particular need to bolster democratic reform in
Peru and in ''precarious'' Haiti. She also said she sought regional
support from Argentina for a U.S. plan to help Colombia fight drug
production.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problems of Colombia are not just of Colombia, but for the
region,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
