<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton spokesman seeks encounter with Rep. Rick Lazio  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP)- You never know who you're going to meet on the
streets of New York - especially during a political campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On a Harlem street Wednesday, Rep. Rick Lazio brushed off an
encounter with Hillary Rodham Clinton's press spokesman, who
arrived waving a copy of the Clintons' property tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   Two blocks earlier, Lazio had halted his bus and jumped out to
greet influential Harlem minister Calvin Butts, who shook hands
with the congressman but insisted that he has not endorsed and may
not endorse either candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, the Clinton campaign's top spokesman, was
rebuffed in his effort to meet Lazio face to face after the Long
Island Republican spoke at a ''Harlem Week 2000 Senior Jubilee'' at
the National Black Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh well,'' Wolfson said after Lazio - accompanied by a cadre
of supporters, staffers, police officers and others - was whisked
past Wolfson on the sidewalk outside the theater and into his
''Mainstream Express'' motor coach.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was starting his third cross-state bus tour since entering
the U.S. Senate contest against Clinton in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congressman Lazio said yesterday that he would release his
taxes in 15 minutes if we could show what Mrs. Clinton had paid in
New York taxes,'' Wolfson said. ''I was just here to try and hand
Congressman Lazio Mrs. Clinton and the president's property tax
returns. Security prevented me from doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has been criticized by Democrats for not releasing copies
of his income tax returns -- something he has promised to do by the
end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday at an appearance in Queens, Lazio was asked about the
tax returns and quipped that he'd ''be willing to release, in the
next 15 minutes, all of my New York state tax returns if she's
willing to do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The comment was meant as a jab at Clinton, who only moved to the
state earlier this year and has not paid New York income taxes yet.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson's appearance -- with property tax receipts from the
Clinton home in Chappaqua -- was the Clinton campaign's answer to
the Lazio remark.
</P>
<P>
   ''Howard must have gotten tired distorting Congressman Lazio's
record from behind his desk and decided to take his act on the
road,'' said Lazio campaign spokesman Patrick McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio received a polite, albeit reserved, welcome in his speech
to the Harlem senior citizens event.
</P>
<P>
   ''Harlem is not traditionally known as a bastion of
Republicanism,'' he said afterward. ''But it's important for me to
be here and for me to make the case. I feel most comfortable in the
areas where Republicans are not often present. I want to make sure
that every community feels ... that I am reaching out to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Butts, the pastor of the Abbyssinian Baptist Church, spotted
Lazio's bus en route to the event. Lazio stopped and greeted the
pastor, who also serves as president of the State University of New
York at Old Westbury.
</P>
<P>
   ''I respect his relationship with a great many of the
constituents out in Suffolk County,'' Butts said. ''I've had the
occasion of speaking before a prayer breakfast that he's held and
some of the leading African-Americans out there, as well as others,
have spoken very highly of him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Butts said he has not endorsed either Lazio or Clinton and
may not.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Lazio toured a community center in Nanuet in Rockland
County. He later attended the Delaware County Agricultural Fair in
Walton on Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-16-00 1948 </TRAILER>
