<DOCNO> APW20000816.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Issues Mideast Travel Warning  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department on Wednesday warned
Americans in Israel, the West Bank and the Gaza Strip of ''an
increased possibility for terrorist attacks'' in those areas.
</P>
<P>
   The department said in a statement that there is no reason to
believe that there is a specific threat directed against Americans,
but that all Americans there should be more careful about security.
</P>
<P>
   Officials suggest travelers be more alert to their surroundings
and report suspicious activity to the police. Also, they should
avoid public buses and exercise caution in the vicinity of bus
stops and crowded areas.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly Palestinian-American man was killed by Israeli
soldiers on Wednesday after the man fired his pistol, thinking that
robbers were breaking into his house.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority called the incident a ''crime,'' and
the commander of the Israeli soldiers on patrol said the man's home
was not the target of their sweep, but would not disclose their
mission.
</P>
<P>
   There is no indication that the State Department warning was
related to Wednesday's incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
