<HEADLINE> India Govt Removes Charges on Group  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRAS, India (AP) -- An Indian state government withdrew
criminal charges Wednesday against five members of an extremist
organization -- a demand put forward by an elusive bandit who
kidnapped a veteran Indian movie star three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnapper, Veerappan, had demanded that the five members of
the secessionist Tamil National Liberation Army be freed. The Tamil
Nadu state government dropped charges against the five, but said it
will only release them after Veerappan frees some of his hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan, 56, who goes by only one name, kidnapped actor
Rajkumar and three companions from Rajkumar's vacation home last
month. A special emissary negotiating with Veerappan for the
government left Wednesday for the bandit's jungle hide-out.
</P>
<P>
   The visit is significant since the state government has rejected
some of the bandit's demands, including making Tamil the only
language of instruction in Tamil Nadu State and referring a water
dispute between Karnataka and Tamil Nadu states to the
International Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The release of Rajkumar is expected to take some time.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan is wanted for killing at least 130 policemen,
slaughtering elephants and felling thousands of sandalwood trees.
He has long eluded capture.
</P>
</TEXT>
