<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Camps Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Kurt Warner is getting a lot of rest this week due to
a sore
arm, although the St. Louis Rams' MVP quarterback doesn't appear
concerned.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''As many times as we throw in camp and as many reps as I've
taken, it's normal to get some type of soreness,'' Warner said
Wednesday. ''We're just trying to attack it while the problem is
small so it feels good come Monday night in the opener.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner didn't practice Tuesday or Wednesday and was hopeful of
getting on the field on Thursday, although coach Mike Martz talked
earlier this week of shutting him down until Saturday's exhibition
game against the Buffalo Bills.
</P>
<P>
   He's played sparingly in the preseason, and won't get more than
one quarter of work against the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ''If that,'' Martz said. ''If you're not careful, he's going to
have a dead arm the rest of the season. He's at the point where his
arm is extremely tired, and this is when you get problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason Warner isn't worried is that he had a sore
arm the last half of last season. He never mentioned it during the
Rams' drive to their Super Bowl victory over the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Actually, I had the same type of stiffness and soreness for
probably the last eight weeks of the season and into the playoffs,
and it was just something we treated every day,'' Warner said.
''But it never became a problem and it's something I can definitely
play with.''
Dolphins:
</P>
<P>
   Jim Druckenmiller, a former first-round draft pick, was waived
Wednesday after losing a battle with journeyman Mike Quinn for a
job as the team's third quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller, 27, hasn't thrown a pass in a regular-season game
since 1997, his rookie season with San Francisco. He was taken with
the 26th pick in the draft that year by the 49ers, then traded in
September 1999 to Miami for a seventh-round pick in this year's
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point, I don't believe that Jim could challenge for
the starting job,'' coach Dave Wannstedt said in a statement. ''So
I wanted to make this move to give Jim a chance to explore other
options in the league.''
Packers:
</P>
<P>
   With lingering tendinitis in his throwing arm, Brett Favre said
he ''easily could be'' out of the Packers' lineup for their last
two preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   Favre, who hasn't practiced in a week, said it was too soon to
tell whether his streak of 125 consecutive regular-season starts --
longest in NFL history by a quarterback -- is in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've played a long time, and I've been fortunate not to have
injuries,'' the three-time MVP said. ''This isn't something I'm
used to, but it's part of the game. I'd much rather be out
practicing with the teammates, but I guess it had to come some
time. I'm just trying to deal with it.''
Browns:
</P>
<P>
   Backup quarterback Ty Detmer was officially placed on injured
reserve Wednesday, making him ineligible to return this season.
</P>
<P>
   Detmer injured his Achilles' tendon during Saturday's preseason
game against Chicago. He had surgery Monday and will need up to
eight months for injury rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle Jeremy McKinney also was placed on injured
reserve.
Falcons:
</P>
<P>
   Starting defensive end Brady Smith will not play in Friday
night's preseason game against the San Diego Chargers because of a
groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, injured Tuesday during a pass rush drill, was still being
evaluated Wednesday by team doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Three other Falcons are out due to injury: tackle Ryan
Johanningmeir (back), tackle Ephraim Salaam (knee) and linebacker
Jon Hesse (neck). In addition, linebacker Brian Smith has been
placed on the reserve/non-football injury list. Smith dislocated
his knee this spring while playing for the Scottish Claymores of
NFL Europe.
Jaguars:
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville acquired guard Brenden Stai from Kansas City for an
undisclosed draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   ''Brenden Stai is a guy we have great experience with,'' Jaguars
coach Tom Coughlin said Wednesday. ''We played against him when he
was in Pittsburgh, and we know him as an outstanding blocker, a
tough guy and an outstanding tempo guy on the practice field.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4, 312-pounder from Nebraska started 59 of 68 games
he played since 1995, when he was selected in the third round of
the NFL draft by the Steelers.
Giants:
</P>
<P>
   Second-year halfback Sean Bennett has a problem with his right
knee that will sideline him a week or two, jeopardizing his
availability for the season-opener against Arizona on Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett had an MRI on the knee Tuesday and coach Jim Fassel said
Wednesday that he still needed more information from the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are concerned a few extra things are going on,'' Fassel
said. ''But they are still telling me it will probably be another
week or two. He needs to strengthen it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett also has been bothered by an injury to the thigh just
above the knee.
49ers:
</P>
<P>
   Steve Young visited training camp and chatted briefly with his
successor, Jeff Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Young casually walked on to the 49ers' practice field at the
University of the Pacific, and it wasn't long before the small
crowd that was gathered noticed and started yelling ''Steve!''
</P>
<P>
   The seven-time Pro Bowl selection, who took the 49ers to a Super
Bowl title in 1995, retired in June after missing most of last
season with his fourth concussion in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in camp, Garcia had suggested to reporters that Young
was not very helpful to him last season. The local media seized on
the comments, and Garcia countered that his words had been blown
out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia later left phone messages with Young to explain himself
and clear the air. Young called the situation a ''non-issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
