<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clues scarce in crash that forced Broward grandmother into swamp  </HEADLINE>
By TERRY SPENCER
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) - Investigators have few clues in the
hit-and-run accident that forced an 83-year-old woman off a 40-foot
bridge and into a swamp, where she survived for three days before
her rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives scraped paint chips from the trunk of Tillie Tooter's
Toyota and collected headlight glass from Interstate 595, hoping to
match it to a suspect's car if one is found, said Florida Highway
Patrol Lt. John Bagnardi.
</P>
<P>
   The FHP received several calls with possible leads since Tooter
was discovered Tuesday inside her car, which was suspended in trees
a foot above the water. So far, none have panned out, Bagnardi
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are looking for a needle in a haystack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tooter remained in serious condition Wednesday at
Broward General Medical Center recovering from dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ralph Guarneri said kidney problems caused by Tooter's
dehydration have been corrected and her blood chemistry is almost
back to normal. He is also treating the hundreds of ant and
mosquito bites the Pembroke Pines widow suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Simms, Tooter's daughter, and Lori Simms, her
granddaughter, said Tooter's strength continues to amaze them.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's laughing. She is starting to get back into her
spirits,'' said Lori Simms, a Marlboro, N.J. resident.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Simms, also from Marlboro, said her mother is angry that
the other driver didn't stop to help her or call police.
</P>
<P>
   ''How could anybody be so cruel as to hit somebody and then run
away?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tooter, a former hairstylist, electrologist, bookkeeper and
garment worker, was struck from behind and forced off the bridge
early Saturday as she drove to Fort Lauderdale/Hollywood
International Airport to pick up her Lori Simms and Simms'
boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   A thicket of mangrove and willow trees cushioned her fall and
kept the car suspended about a foot above the alligator- and
snake-infested swamp.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an extensive search, she remained missing until
15-year-old Justin Vannelli, who was cleaning the highway for his
dad's company, noticed an indentation in the trees, looked over the
bridge and saw Tooter's car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
