<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protesters Disrupt Chilean Senate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Chanting slogans in support of Gen.
Augusto Pinochet, protesters on Wednesday interrupted a Chilean
Senate session devoted to discussing the embattled former
dictator's 17-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   Police ordered the Pinochet backers to leave a debate on the
causes and consequences of Pinochet's 1973 coup and the human
rights abuses committed by his regime. The demonstrators left
peacefully, still chanting.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Supreme Court stripped Pinochet of his
legislative immunity from prosecution, clearing the way for a trial
on human rights charges. According to a government report, 3,197
people were killed or disappeared for political reasons under
Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's senate session was called by right-wing senators to
discuss the coup, in which Pinochet overthrew elected Marxist
President Salvador Allende.
</P>
<P>
   The four-hour debate was seen as the beginning of a right-wing
campaign to promote political support for the legally embattled
former dictator. As expected, it developed along the lines that
have divided Chile for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Many on the right insist the coup prevented Allende's
Marxist-dominated coalition from establishing a totalitarian,
Cuban-style regime. Under Allende's three-year government, Chile
plunged into political and economic crisis with often violent
political conflict, acute shortages and 500 percent inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Leftist politicians say the Allende government was responsible
for errors, but that the Pinochet regime was guilty of horrors.
</P>
<P>
   The government of President Ricardo Lagos, a socialist jailed
under Pinochet, stayed away from Wednesday's debate, warning that
it would only promote more division. The debate, which may resume
Thursday, is not expected to reach any conclusion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-16-00 2127 </TRAILER>
