<HEADLINE> Pitcher Tim Hudson OKs New A's Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- The Oakland Athletics signed All-Star
right-hander Tim Hudson to a four-year contract extension worth $9
million on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson, 25, is fourth in the AL with 13 wins, and has a 4.79 ERA
in 23 starts for Oakland this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's nice to know he's going to be around for a while,'' A's
manager Art Howe said. ''He's special. He's proven his mettle for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson is 24-6 in 44 career starts, and his .800 winning
percentage is the best in Oakland history.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously I'm very happy. The organization has given me the
opportunity and had the confidence in me to work something out,''
Hudson said. ''Hopefully I can help this team out for years to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Contract talks began at the end of spring training, and heated
up once the A's signed third baseman Eric Chavez to a four-year
deal earlier in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to wait my turn,'' Hudson said. ''We all signed
four-year deals, so we know we'll be together for a while. That
gives us a chance to build some chemistry between us.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal extends Hudson's contract through the 2004 season, when
he will be eligible for free agency. The A's have 10 players signed
beyond the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson is the fourth player to sign a four-year extension with
Oakland this season. In addition to Chavez, shortstop Miguel Tejada
and outfielder Ben Grieve signed deals earlier this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
