<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Rethinking Congo Mission  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- A year ago, the United Nations was talking
about a major peacekeeping operation in Congo with a minimum of
25,000 soldiers. Now, it's reevaluating plans to send 5,500
observers to the central African nation because there is no peace
to keep.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Security Council on Wednesday,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said he wants to examine what role
U.N. military observers can play when a year-old cease-fire is
crumbling and U.N. staff in Congo are vilified and face severe
restrictions on their freedom of movement.
</P>
<P>
   He asked the 15-member council to extend the mandate of the U.N.
mission, known as MONUC, which is due to expire on Aug. 31, for one
month until Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said the extension will give him time to undertake a
''substantial reevaluation'' and consider the implications of
recent developments. Among other things, he singled out this week's
summit of African leaders in Zambia, which failed to agree on
measures to revive the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting in Congo began two years ago. Rebel forces backed by
Rwanda and Uganda have been trying to oust Congolese President
Laurent Kabila, who has received support from Angola, Namibia and
Zimbabwe. The Rwanda-Uganda alliance later fell apart, with each
country backing rival rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
   When the warring parties signed a cease-fire in Lusaka, Zambia,
last summer, U.N. officials envisioned an eventual peacekeeping
operation with a minimum of 25,000 soldiers. That would be the
largest U.N. peacekeeping mission in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In late February, the Security Council agreed to send 500
military observers backed by 5,037 U.N. troops to monitor the
cease-fire and lay the groundwork for a possible full-fledged
peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   But deployment was conditioned on security guarantees for the
troops. So far, only 264 military observers and about 15
international staff have been sent to Congo because of heavy
fighting and security problems.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general and the United States blame the Congolese
government for stonewalling on implementation of the cease-fire.
Annan noted the ''adverse climate'' which is still preventing
deployment of the U.N. observers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The situation is characterized by persistent large-scale
fighting in many parts of the country, severe restrictions imposed
by the government and other parties on the mission's freedom of
movement, the refusal of the government to permit the deployment of
United Nations armed troops,'' he said in the letter. He also noted
''a sustained campaign of vilification conducted against MONUC and
individual members of its staff, which has created a significant
risk to their security.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
