<HEADLINE> Montana Gov. Declares Disaster Area  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON DININNY
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMILTON, Mont. (AP) -- The governor declared the entire state of
Montana a disaster area Wednesday as authorities issued a new
evacuation order for part of the burned, smoke-choked Bitterroot
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster order from Gov. Marc Racicot allows him to tap
state resources and the National Guard to battle wildfires. It was
scheduled to take effect at midnight Wednesday, said Anastasia
Burton, spokeswoman for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The order primarily allows use of the National Guard anywhere in
the state, officials said. Previous orders by Racicot allowed use
of guard units only in specified areas.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million acres of forest, brush and grass had been
blackened by the 86 large wildland fires burning Wednesday in 13
Western states, according to the National Interagency Fire Center
in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Montana's 25 largest active fires accounted for nearly half of
that total acreage, the agency said. So far this year, more than
2,000 fires have burned 457,000 acres statewide.
</P>
<P>
   A deadline of Thursday night was set for people to move out of a
fire-threatened area south of where other Bitterroot Valley
residents had been allowed to return home.
</P>
<P>
   The latest evacuations were in a large area some 50 miles south
of Hamilton, almost in Idaho, and covered about 100 homes, said Jim
Chinn of the Ravalli County Sheriff's Department.
</P>
<P>
   While residents of some 900 houses have been allowed to return
home, hundreds of others remained out of their homes for a second
week as fires burned on.
</P>
<P>
   A fire south of Helena also triggered evacuations and burned
some land owned by media magnate Ted Turner, who owns four bison
ranches in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Federal land managers are closing the Salmon River and the 2.4
million-acre Frank Church-River of No Return Wilderness in Idaho to
public use effective Thursday. Fires were burning over 182,000
acres in the protected area.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, 55 people had been evacuated from the southern Black
Hills, south of Hot Springs, S.D., where a 7,000-acre blaze was 60
percent contained. It is unlikely that they will be allowed to
return home before the fire is fully contained, which is expected
on Friday, said Forest Service spokesman Terry Padilla.
</P>
<P>
   In Wyoming, a wildfire that forced hundreds to evacuate a lodge
and a campground continued spreading and prompted officials to
close Yellowstone National Park's south entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The fire danger extended to Alaska, where the National Weather
Service on Tuesday issued a ''red flag warning,'' its most severe
fire warning, for the Kenai Peninsula and Kodiak Island.
</P>
<P>
   Humidity in the area was only about 17 percent, significantly
lower than the usual 50 percent, and state fire managers were
concerned because many of their crews were battling fires in the
Lower 48 states.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Interagency Fire Center: http://www.nifc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service: http://www.fs.fed.us/fire/news.shtml
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-16-00 2148 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000816.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers' Kapler Ends Hitting Streak  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Texas' Gabe Kapler failed to extend his
28-game hitting streak when he was 0-for-4 against the New York
Yankees on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The streak was the longest in the majors this season, but still
only halfway to Joe DiMaggio's record 56-game streak from 1941.
</P>
<P>
   In his last chance to extend the streak, Kapler struck out in
the eighth inning against Randy Choate. He also flew out to right
and grounded out twice, one of those a backhanded stab by Yankees
shortstop Derek Jeter in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler had extended the hitting streak three times in his final
at-bat, including Tuesday night with a single in the eighth inning
against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Kapler failed to extend his hitting streak, the
Rangers snapped their 10-game losing streak to the Yankees with a
5-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   During the 28-game streak, a Rangers franchise record, Kapler
batted .375 (42-for-112) with six homers and 21 RBI. He had had a
hit in every game since July 17.
</P>
<P>
   The best previous hitting streak in Texas/Washington franchise
history was a 24-game hitting streak by Mickey Rivers from Aug. 14
through Sept. 9, 1980.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
