<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plane Hijacked, Robbed in Brazil  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Armed men hijacked a Brazilian
airliner with 72 people aboard on Wednesday and forced the pilot to
land at an isolated airstrip in southern Brazil, then fled with at
least $3.3 million in stolen cash, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 66 passengers were tourists from Italy, France and
Japan returning from the famous Iguacu Falls on the border with
Argentina, police and airline officials said. They and the six crew
members on the Vasp Airline jet were all unharmed, said Federal
Police officer Roberto Viana dos Santos.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the passengers were not released.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the hijackers pointed a pistol at the head of the pilot
and forced him to land. He also fired a shot in the cabin to scare
the pilot,'' dos Santos said.
</P>
<P>
   There were conflicting reports as to where the hijackers got the
money. Officers said some was stolen from an armored car in the
southern city of Foz do Iguacu, where the flight originated.
</P>
<P>
   Other reports, however, said the money was stolen from the
plane's cargo hold. The money was being transported for local
banks.
</P>
<P>
   At least five men armed with handguns boarded the Boeing 737
bound from Foz do Iguacu to Curitiba, both cities in southern
Parana state, dos Santos said.
</P>
<P>
   The men boarded as passengers. It was not clear how they got on
the plane carrying weapons, but police were investigating airport
employees for possible involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The hijackers told the pilot to land at a runway surrounded by
nothing but cattle ranches and sugar cane plantations in an
isolated part of Parana state, about 400 miles southwest of Rio,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   After the plane landed, the hijackers jumped into a Ford Ranger
that was waiting for them at the edge of the paved landing strip.
They then sped away, police said.
</P>
<P>
   After the hijackers were gone, the pilot flew the plane to the
nearest airport at the city of Londrina, 50 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Police were still searching for the hijackers on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have no clue regarding the identity of the robbers,''
Parana state police captain Sergio Dalbem said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
