<HEADLINE> By The Associated Press  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Text of speech by Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., at
the
Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles on Wednesday.
Transcription by eMediaMillWorks Inc.:
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm proud to be here representing the great state of New York
and I'm proud to be here as the Democratic chair of the
Congressional Women's Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, our caucus is the face of America. We don't
have to talk inclusion, we are inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   We are over 40 strong with more to come. But we realize we stand
on the shoulders of the giants who served before us, great
Democratic congresswomen - Barbara Jordan, Patricia Schroeder,
Shirley Chisholm, Liz Holtzman, Bella Abzug and, of course, from
the last time our party broke through a barrier that stood for too
long, Geraldine Ferraro.
</P>
<P>
   They opened the doors of opportunity for America's women. We are
doing our best to follow in that great tradition. We remember when
women could not get credit in their own names, when women could not
serve on juries, when equal pay for equal work wasn't even a
slogan. And we remember all too well when being pregnant was
grounds for dismissal. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   We've come a long way, especially over the last eight years.
I've worked with Al Gore. I've gotten to know him. I believe in
him. Women of America, Al Gore stands with us.
</P>
<P>
   From the Family and Medical Leave Act to the Violence Against
Women Act, from doubling breast cancer research to casting the
deciding vote to get guns off the streets, Al Gore stands with us.
Al Gore stands with America's women.
</P>
<P>
   But many of our battles still are not won. Democratic women will
help Al Gore win these battles.
</P>
<P>
   But let me underscore one issue, protecting a woman's right to
choose.
</P>
<P>
   Mark my words. Choice hangs by a single vote on the Supreme
Court. If the other side wins, women will lose their right to
choose. It's not that we might lose; we will lose. Women of
America, Democrats, Republicans, independents, we cannot let that
happen.
</P>
<P>
   And in the words of another New York woman, Eleanor Roosevelt,
it's up to the women. Women make a difference. We've always made a
difference. Let's elect Al Gore. When Al Gore wins, we win, women
win, America wins.
</P>
<P>
   And now, I'm proud to introduce the vice-chair of the
Congressional Women's Caucus for women from the great state of
California, Juanita Millender-McDonald.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
