<HEADLINE> Wrestler Considers Run For Office  </HEADLINE>
By CHELSEA J. CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Rock for Prez? Don't rule it out.
</P>
<P>
   The World Wrestling Federation champion, in an encore to his
appearance at the GOP convention in Philadelphia, told an audience
at the Democratic National Convention that he might consider a run
for office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jesse Ventura has made that jump and done fairly well,'' he
said, although he added that his political aspirations would reach
beyond the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   ''With all due respect to Jesse, I would say The Rock has to be
synonymous with, say, president,'' he told a cheering crowd at an
event to promote the WWF's ''Smackdown Your Vote!'' campaign to
register 14 million new voters.
</P>
<P>
   The hulking wrestler even got a suggestion for a running mate:
woman wrestler Chyna, who appeared with him.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Just when you thought it was safe to swim the political waters,
Oscar-winning actor Richard Dreyfuss warned California Democrats on
Wednesday that Republicans can't be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Jaws'' star listed Social Security, education, abortion
and health care as issues too important to trust to the GOP ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ''George Bush doesn't get them and Dick Cheney doesn't like
them,'' said Dreyfuss, known for his roles in ''American Graffiti''
and ''Close Encounters of the Third Kind'' and star of the
soon-to-be released movie ''The Crew.''
</P>
<P>
   He urged cheering Democratic National Convention delegates to
''go get 'em'' by keeping control of the White House and picking up
seven seats to regain control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Republicans in the House of Representatives are the only
obstacles, the only stop signs that are keeping America from its
own future,'' Dreyfuss said at the California delegation's
breakfast at the Westin Bonaventure Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Politics aside, Arnold Schwarzenegger, wants to terminate
problems faced by inner-city youth.
</P>
<P>
   The outspoken Republican and founder of the Inner-City Games
Foundation took a tour Wednesday of the first of 14 cities that now
host his program by visiting Los Angeles' Hollenbeck Youth Center.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the city is crawling with Democrats for the
party's national convention. Schwarzenegger said the program is
about helping kids do the right thing after school.
</P>
<P>
   ''Forget the Democrats,'' he said. ''It's not a Republican
issue. It's not a Democrat issue. It's an issue facing America.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzenegger was joined by seven mayors from across the
country, his NBC-reporter wife Maria Shriver and other political
dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   In the center's gymnasium, Schwarzenegger leapt back into his
role as the undercover teacher in the movie ''Kindergarten Cop'' to
cheer on a group of girls on the balance beam.
</P>
<P>
   ''Beau-ti-ful,'' he said with some claps.
</P>
<P>
   In a weight room with a 12-foot likeness of him painted on the
wall, Schwarzenegger filled in as weight trainer: ''No cheating
here -- all the way down to the legs!''
</P>
<P>
   And he promised the youngsters: ''I'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Actor Sean Penn was among hundreds of supporters greeting Al
Gore and running mate Joseph Lieberman as the vice president
arrived for the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd cheered the arrival Air Force Two on Wednesday
afternoon, Penn, wearing a rumpled black suit and cowboy boots,
stood in front with his arms crossed.
</P>
<P>
   A member of California Gov. Gray Davis' staff escorted Penn to a
red-carpet receiving area to greet the Democratic presidential
ticket, jokingly advising him: ''You are standing with the
Lieberman family, so try to look like one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ''No 'Dead Man Walking' jokes,'' a Democratic activist mumbled,
referring to Gore's wooden reputation and one of Penn's starring
roles.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Stevie Wonder had a packed convention hall swaying and clapping
along when he opened Wednesday evening's convention session with a
medley version of ''The Star-Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   First, he told the audience, ''We at the end of the 20th century
are about to cast our final vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ''History tonight reminds us we must redeem the dream of (Martin
Luther) King,'' Wonder said, drawing a huge cheer from the
delegates. He spoke of an ''innervision, a new millennium
democracy, a vision of who we are and what America has come to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Let us keep moving forward ever, backwards never,'' Wonder
said, and raised his harmonica to begin the national anthem.
Accompanied by a gospel choir, the medley closed with the lines
''we see an America, a united America.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Rocker David Crosby nearly upstaged Andrew Cuomo during a
Creative Coalition ceremony honoring the U.S. housing secretary for
his public service.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby, the singer and songwriter from Crosby, Stills and Nash,
posed for pictures and handed out autographs to star-struck
celebrities, delegates and media.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo encouraged the celebrity-filled reception, which included
actress Sharon Lawrence, actors Harry Hamlin and Daniel Stern, and
Bianca Jagger, at the Los Angeles Public Library to use their star
status to help curb homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby agreed, but said celebrities had to take responsibility
for their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have the ability to focus media attention on the
issues because of who we are,'' he said. ''But that ability
requires us to ... do our part, to take responsibility for how we
get the word out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
