<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, Aug. 16, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
L.A. Protesters Decry Cop Brutality
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Police faced off with about 2,500 demonstrators outside
the Democratic National Convention today after the protesters, chanting of
police brutality, marched from police headquarters to the convention site.
Trouble broke out as officers tried to get a truck through an intersection
blocked by the protesters, who then began throwing bottles and other objects.
Protesters have been marching for various causes here since last weekend.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sen. John McCain Has Melanoma
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Arizona Sen. John McCain has been diagnosed with a second
bout of melanoma, the most dangerous form of skin cancer. McCain, who waged a
spirited contest for the Republican nomination against George W. Bush, has
canceled a number of campaign appearances and expects to undergo surgery, aides
said. ''During a routine examination two unrelated spots were discovered on Sen.
John McCain. One on his left temple, the other on his left arm. The spots were
confirmed to be melanomas,'' said a statement issued today by his office.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gephardt: Democrats Must Win Congress
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Calling Republicans ''intolerant of other views,'' House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said today that Democrats must win control of
Congress if a Democratic White House's policies are to have a chance to become
law. ''We can pass laws that help people, or we can continue to frustrate the
hopes and dreams of working families,'' Gephardt told delegates to the
Democratic National Convention. The Missouri lawmaker, likely to become speaker
if his party wins a House majority in November, called Vice President Al Gore
''a good man'' who cares about his family and country.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tipper Gore Goes on 'Tonight Show'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. (AP) -- Jay Leno teased and prodded, but Tipper Gore wasn't
going to dish any dirt about hubby Al on ''The Tonight Show.'' Comparing her
marriage to the vice president to a Disney movie -- the couple met when they
were teen-agers -- Leno asked if they'd really fallen for each other right away.
''I've always told him it was love at first sight, and it was. ... I don't think
we should change it tonight,'' she replied. Although known as the gregarious one
in the Gore marriage, the vice president's wife seemed subdued with Leno.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russia Asks for Help Saving Sub Crew
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia relented Wednesday and asked for Western aid to reach
116 sailors trapped in a doomed submarine -- the crew of the Kursk, cut off from
the world under the Barents Sea, with air likely dwindling and possibly without
light or heat. A Norwegian ship with a team of divers and a British rescue
mini-sub headed for the site but will take days to get there. Russian rescue
capsules repeatedly descended through the stormy waters Wednesday but, whipped
about by currents, could not latch onto the submarine, lying at a sharp list 354
feet beneath the surface.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FBI To Release E-mail Documents
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The FBI has 3,000 pages of documents about its
''Carnivore'' e-mail surveillance system and expects to begin releasing some to
the public in about 45 days, the Justice Department said today. Additional
releases should follow every 45 days. The Carnivore, which has caused an uproar
among civil libertarians and in Congress, has software that scans and captures
''packets,'' the standard unit of Internet traffic, as they travel through an
internet service provider's network. ''The proposed schedule is far too
open-ended,'' complained David Sobel, general counsel of the private Electronic
Privacy Information Center, which sued under the Freedom of Information Act to
get all the FBI's documents describing the system.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped early Thursday following a decline in the
Dow Jones industrial average on Wall Street. The Nikkei shed 91.98 points to
16,264.05 in the first 30 minutes of trading. Investors turned bearish following
a 58.61-point decline in the Dow Jones industrial average on Wednesday, when the
index closed at 11,008.39. Also in New York, the Nasdaq composite index rose
9.54 points to closed at 3,861.20.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Four-Team Deal Completed in NBA
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- The first four-team trade in NBA history was completed today
when nine players switched teams, with Howard Eisley going to Dallas, Danny
Fortson to Golden State, Donyell Marshall to Utah and Robert Pack to Boston. The
Celtics also get center John ''Hot Rod'' Williams from Dallas, Utah's
first-round pick in 2001 and a ''substantial amount of cash,'' general manager
Chris Wallace said. Boston also sent guard Dana Barros to Dallas.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
End AP NewsBrief
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
