<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Backers Plot Connecticut Strategy  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW DALY
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) - Amid the hoopla surrounding
Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman's elevation to the national
Democratic stage, Connecticut Republicans countered with a message
of their own Wednesday night: Don't count us out.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting hours before Lieberman accepted his party's
nomination for vice president, undaunted state Republicans said
they are not conceding the Nutmeg State to Lieberman and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans held a strategy meeting designed to unite supporters
of former rivals George W. Bush and John McCain and find ways to
counteract the bounce Democrats expect from Lieberman's presence
atop the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Malcynsky, Bush's Connecticut coordinator, conceded that
Lieberman will ''energize'' local Democrats and almost certainly
will increase turnout in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the presence of Lieberman alone does not guarantee
that Connecticut will go into the Democrats' column this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Polls released before Lieberman was chosen as Gore's running
mate, showed Gore and Bush in a virtual dead heat in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the end of the day, Joe Lieberman doesn't save Al Gore,''
Malcynsky told about 30 Republicans gathered at Bush's Connecticut
headquarters in New Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those in attendance supported McCain during the
sometimes bitter GOP primary, and the differences between the two
camps were apparent Wednesday night. Several McCain supporters
complained about a recently approved rule change allowing state
party leaders to choose delegates to the next national Republican
convention, instead of apportioning them on a ''winner take all''
basis as before.
</P>
<P>
   ''By changing the rules, you sent me out the door,'' said Neal
Yates, a McCain supporter from New Hartford. ''I don't see where
the Republican party wants me involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But Malcynsky said the Bush campaign is actively courting
McCain's supporters, hoping to tap into the grass-roots
organization that helped the Arizona senator beat Bush in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really see this as the best opportunity in a long time to
bring new people into the tent and revitalize the party
organization in the state,'' said Malcynsky, a lobbyist and
longtime party stalwart.
</P>
<P>
   Some prominent McCain supporters agreed.
</P>
<P>
   '' I thought it was a good meeting,'' said Ben Davol, one of
three McCain coordinators in the state. ''I think we're moving
forward in unifying the party to elect George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Davol and other GOP leaders called the dustup over the rules
change a minor issue that will be resolved long before the next
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Nancy L. Johnson, R-6th District, called the rules
change ''ridiculous,'' but said it had little to do with the
purpose of the meeting: delivering Connecticut for George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can win this on substance,'' Johnson said, criticizing
Lieberman for backtracking on some long-held views since being
named as Gore's running mate. Specifically, she accused Lieberman
of flip-flopping on Social Security, affirmative action, school
vouchers and even his signature issue: the ''moral degradation'' of
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of getting bogged down in procedural arguments or
internal disputes, Republicans should focus on a simple message,
Johnson said: ''Lieberman is a fine guy, but too bad he's changed
his stripes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-16-00 2204 </TRAILER>
