<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Asks for Help Rescuing Sub  </HEADLINE>
By JIM HEINTZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Increasingly desperate to reach 116 sailors
trapped in a doomed submarine, Russia relented Wednesday and asked
for Western aid after its rescue teams were driven back by strong
currents on the pitch-black sea bottom.
</P>
<P>
   But help may come too late for the crew of the Kursk, cut off
from the world under the Barents Sea, with air likely dwindling and
possibly without light or heat. A Norwegian ship with a team of
divers and a British rescue mini-sub headed for the site but will
take days to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Russian rescue capsules repeatedly descended through the stormy
waters Wednesday but, whipped about by currents, could not latch
onto the submarine, lying at a sharp list 354 feet deep beneath the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   After insisting for days that Western aid was inferior and was
not needed, the Russian government asked Britain and Norway to send
equipment and divers.
</P>
<P>
   The turnabout apparently came after President Vladimir Putin
spoke with President Clinton on Wednesday and ordered his navy to
seek help.
</P>
<P>
   The navy said it had no idea of conditions inside the Kursk,
including whether any of the crew were alive.
</P>
<P>
   The submarine sank after an apparent explosion Saturday.
Throughout the nerve-flaying disaster, Russian officials have
repeatedly given contradictory reports of whether rescuers had
detected any signs of life from within the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   There is also no clear picture of how much air may remain aboard
or whether backup systems were working on the boat, which is at
least partially flooded.
</P>
<P>
   If survivors are trying to husband oxygen by reducing its flow
from reserve tanks, they could be lightheaded, confused or
unconscious. If power systems are not operating, the inside of the
Kursk would be pitch-black and very cold.
</P>
<P>
   Britain on Wednesday flew a LR5 mini-submarine to the Norwegian
port city of Trondheim for shipping to the disaster site. Some 15
people were working under bright lights in the early morning hours
Thursday loading the mini-sub onto a red Norwegian ship in
Trondheim, 280 miles north of the capital, Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   The trip would take about 52 hours, getting the rescue craft to
the scene by Saturday, Norwegian officials said. The LR5 can hold
16 passengers and may be able to connect to the Kursk's hatch,
though it was not sure the hatches will match.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear why the British team or the Norwegian divers
did not fly to any of the Russian military bases located much
closer to where the Kursk went down.
</P>
<P>
   The developments suggested Russia was still halfhearted about
accepting Western help, especially from members of NATO, which
Moscow sees as a threat despite the end of the Cold War. But
British Defense Ministry officials said they factored in the
distance and the type of ship needed in choosing the Norwegian ship
for transporting the safety equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Norway option provided the quickest and safest way of
getting our equipment to the scene,'' a ministry spokesman in
London said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian ship with a dozen civilian divers, which was
diverted Wednesday from an offshore oil field, will take up to two
days to get to the site where the Kursk went down, Norway's Foreign
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vessel is starting to move north,'' Foreign Minister
Thorbjoern Jagland said in a television interview. ''These are
professional divers who can contribute in many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Arctic waters of the Barents, the 20-ship Russian navy
operation was battered by strong winds and surging waves.
</P>
<P>
   Underwater, currents jarred the delicate maneuvers of the rescue
capsules, and muddy maters reduced visibility to mere inches even
under spotlights, said navy spokesman Capt. Igor Babenko.
</P>
<P>
   The latest rescue attempts involved a capsule called the Bester,
a 50-ton vehicle with a crew of two or three and able to take up to
20 evacuees. Officials said they hoped the Bester would be better
able to fight the heavy currents than a smaller, lighter capsule
that had been used earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the navy, Adm. Vladimir Kuroyedov, said Wednesday he
was more confident about the chances of success and that rescue
operations would continue until at least Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now I am feeling more confidence that the operation to rescue
the Kursk's crew will yield a result,'' he told the ITAR-Tass news
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Kuroyedov said nothing had been heard from inside the Kursk, but
the navy's deputy chief of staff, Vice Admiral Vladislav Ilyin,
maintained there had been contact, although he gave no details.
</P>
<P>
   Russian navy officials told The Associated Press on Wednesday
that they lost contact with the Kursk on Saturday, despite earlier
statements that contact was lost Sunday. The submarine suffered
extensive damage after an explosion in the torpedo compartment at
the front of the vessel, but the cause was not clear, the navy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, ITAR-Tass quoted an unnamed Pentagon official as
saying U.S. submarines following the ill-fated exercise detected
two explosions at the site of the disaster, with the second one
even more powerful than the first.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Navy's press service said in response that top
commanders would not confirm such information. It added that a
government investigative commission would determine the cause of
the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing any survivors to the surface could take hours, with a
slow ascent needed to prevent the potentially crippling or fatal
decompression sickness.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers were also considering using giant pontoons to float the
vessel. Another proposal called for raising the submarine to a
vertical position so part of it protruded from the water.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the Kursk's two nuclear reactors had been
switched off and it was not carrying nuclear weapons. Norway said
there was no sign of a radiation leak in the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-16-00 2204 </TRAILER>
